WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:04.630
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress, in Washington, D.C.

00:00:13.130 --> 00:00:15.250
&gt;&gt; Susan Vita: Good
morning, everyone.

00:00:15.250 --> 00:00:18.820
As one of my colleagues said,

00:00:18.820 --> 00:00:21.180
"Monday morning,
early in December.

00:00:21.180 --> 00:00:24.270
Is anyone going to come?"

00:00:24.270 --> 00:00:26.810
So it's really fabulous
to see every --

00:00:26.810 --> 00:00:33.610
all of these seats filled,
and so much just excitement

00:00:33.610 --> 00:00:36.350
from the conversations
that are going on.

00:00:36.350 --> 00:00:38.000
I think this is -- bodes well

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:40.870
for what we're going
to do today.

00:00:40.870 --> 00:00:45.190
And I wanted to welcome you
to the Library of Congress.

00:00:45.190 --> 00:00:51.550
You are the perfect
audience, patrons and lovers

00:00:51.550 --> 00:00:54.420
of the arts and the humanities.

00:00:54.420 --> 00:00:58.520
And this is the oldest
cultural institution

00:00:58.520 --> 00:01:00.890
in the entire country.

00:01:00.890 --> 00:01:04.610
And so I think it's a
perfect venue for a spotlight

00:01:04.610 --> 00:01:07.950
on arts education symposium.

00:01:07.950 --> 00:01:11.710
I am pleased to recognize the
District of Columbia Commission

00:01:11.710 --> 00:01:14.430
on Arts and Education.

00:01:14.430 --> 00:01:19.660
I am pleased to --
sorry, to recognize the --

00:01:19.660 --> 00:01:24.430
it for its work developing
and promoting local artists

00:01:24.430 --> 00:01:27.610
and organizations,
providing grants, programs,

00:01:27.610 --> 00:01:31.590
education activities
that encourage diverse,

00:01:31.590 --> 00:01:35.190
artistic expression, and
learning opportunities

00:01:35.190 --> 00:01:39.440
for all District of Columbia
residents and visitors

00:01:39.440 --> 00:01:43.340
to experience the rich
culture of our city.

00:01:43.340 --> 00:01:45.940
The Library of Congress,
as I said,

00:01:45.940 --> 00:01:49.050
is the oldest cultural
institution in the country.

00:01:49.050 --> 00:01:52.160
It's more than two
centuries old,

00:01:52.160 --> 00:01:55.710
and I thought I would tell
you a few things about it,

00:01:55.710 --> 00:02:00.560
and why it's a good place
to have this symposium.

00:02:00.560 --> 00:02:06.350
It features 883 miles
of shelving,

00:02:06.350 --> 00:02:14.400
houses 155 million total items.

00:02:14.400 --> 00:02:17.130
It holds 33 million
books written

00:02:17.130 --> 00:02:21.290
in 460 different languages.

00:02:21.290 --> 00:02:26.680
It's home to 68 million
manuscripts, 25 million pieces

00:02:26.680 --> 00:02:30.690
of music, more than
5 million maps,

00:02:30.690 --> 00:02:34.210
over 3.4 million recordings,

00:02:34.210 --> 00:02:39.750
and more than 13.5
million photographs.

00:02:39.750 --> 00:02:44.660
We receive and add
approximately 12,000 items

00:02:44.660 --> 00:02:46.710
to our collection every day.

00:02:46.710 --> 00:02:52.900
And -- so basically, what I am
-- why I'm telling you this is,

00:02:52.900 --> 00:03:00.860
I'm trying to emphasize the fact
that people say library books.

00:03:00.860 --> 00:03:03.260
Well, forget that.

00:03:03.260 --> 00:03:07.390
We do have much more than books,

00:03:07.390 --> 00:03:12.310
and so many of these things
can be used by the people

00:03:12.310 --> 00:03:18.380
that you're helping
to inspire artistic

00:03:18.380 --> 00:03:22.220
and expression in
the humanities.

00:03:22.220 --> 00:03:25.580
Here's -- this is just a
whirlwind listing of a sample

00:03:25.580 --> 00:03:29.490
of what you could
encourage people to use.

00:03:29.490 --> 00:03:32.830
Children's books -- we have
the smallest children's books.

00:03:32.830 --> 00:03:34.130
It's "Old King Cole."

00:03:34.130 --> 00:03:36.660
It is about the size
of a period.

00:03:36.660 --> 00:03:39.410
And we have the largest book.

00:03:39.410 --> 00:03:43.510
It is a five-by-seven book
featuring color images

00:03:43.510 --> 00:03:44.810
of Bhutan.

00:03:44.810 --> 00:03:48.670
So it's -- imagine that it's
as tall as I am, and I'm not --

00:03:48.670 --> 00:03:50.970
it's a lot wider
than I am, thank God.

00:03:56.190 --> 00:03:58.160
The oldest written material

00:03:58.160 --> 00:04:00.820
in the library is a
cuneiform tablet dating

00:04:00.820 --> 00:04:06.400
from 2040 B.C. Comic books --

00:04:06.400 --> 00:04:09.440
we have the world's largest
collection of comic books,

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:14.110
more than 140,000 of them.

00:04:14.110 --> 00:04:16.680
And we also hold the
world's most extensive

00:04:16.680 --> 00:04:18.340
newspaper collection.

00:04:18.340 --> 00:04:23.850
The oldest original newspaper
is from December 29th, 1659.

00:04:23.850 --> 00:04:27.590
We have the papers
of 23 presidents.

00:04:27.590 --> 00:04:30.260
Before people started putting
them in their own buildings,

00:04:30.260 --> 00:04:32.470
we -- this is the
place where they came.

00:04:32.470 --> 00:04:34.080
So we have George Washington --

00:04:34.080 --> 00:04:35.730
everything from George
Washington

00:04:35.730 --> 00:04:38.230
up through Calvin Coolidge.

00:04:38.230 --> 00:04:41.620
We have the Gutenberg
Bible, which is one

00:04:41.620 --> 00:04:47.110
of three perfect vellum
copies in the world.

00:04:47.110 --> 00:04:50.250
More than 50 million
visual materials,

00:04:50.250 --> 00:04:54.190
including the most comprehensive
international collection

00:04:54.190 --> 00:04:57.120
of posters in the world.

00:04:57.120 --> 00:04:59.970
And the most comprehensive
visual record

00:04:59.970 --> 00:05:05.410
of the Civil War -- can you
imagine how important the Civil

00:05:05.410 --> 00:05:09.100
War is, in humanities and the
arts, and fact that we have all

00:05:09.100 --> 00:05:12.740
of this material on the
Civil War, of photographs,

00:05:12.740 --> 00:05:19.340
and band music, and
all sorts of things?

00:05:19.340 --> 00:05:23.010
The Library's Packard Campus
for Audiovisual Conservation

00:05:23.010 --> 00:05:31.760
in Culpepper has 60 -- sorry,
6 million items, including more

00:05:31.760 --> 00:05:34.840
than 3.6 million sound
recordings, and more --

00:05:34.840 --> 00:05:38.350
almost 2 million films.

00:05:38.350 --> 00:05:42.020
And the most comprehensive
collection --

00:05:42.020 --> 00:05:45.890
I'm the chief of the -- I
forgot to introduce myself.

00:05:45.890 --> 00:05:48.370
I'm Susan Vita, the Chief
of the Music Division here

00:05:48.370 --> 00:05:50.340
at the Library of Congress.

00:05:50.340 --> 00:05:53.380
So let me say a couple things
about the music collection.

00:05:53.380 --> 00:06:00.280
We have more than 25 -- it's
the largest music collection

00:06:00.280 --> 00:06:01.580
in the world.

00:06:01.580 --> 00:06:03.870
We have more than
25 million items,

00:06:03.870 --> 00:06:08.570
including 8 million
pieces of sheet music,

00:06:08.570 --> 00:06:10.240
which include all sorts of --

00:06:10.240 --> 00:06:12.560
you can really learn a
lot of things about --

00:06:12.560 --> 00:06:14.780
when you just look
at sheet music.

00:06:14.780 --> 00:06:17.940
Basically, what ads
were people --

00:06:17.940 --> 00:06:21.910
you know, were important
in that time?

00:06:21.910 --> 00:06:23.230
What were the clothes

00:06:23.230 --> 00:06:26.810
that people were
wearing, from the covers?

00:06:26.810 --> 00:06:34.330
We have -- they depict the
sinking of the Titanic,

00:06:34.330 --> 00:06:40.970
and the Triangle Shirtwaist
Fire, 400 songs about baseball,

00:06:40.970 --> 00:06:45.020
more than 13,000
World War I songs.

00:06:45.020 --> 00:06:47.870
The collection includes
an extensive assemblage

00:06:47.870 --> 00:06:50.850
of original manuscripts
by composers

00:06:50.850 --> 00:06:54.770
of the American musical theater,
and the largest collection

00:06:54.770 --> 00:06:58.120
of any one kind of musical
instrument in the world,

00:06:58.120 --> 00:06:59.420
and that is the flute.

00:06:59.420 --> 00:07:04.760
So let me just talk a second
about the musical theater,

00:07:04.760 --> 00:07:08.030
and the connections, and
how you can use the Library.

00:07:08.030 --> 00:07:12.040
If you, for example, were going
to encourage somebody to look

00:07:12.040 --> 00:07:15.960
at "On The Town," we have
Leonard Bernstein's collection.

00:07:15.960 --> 00:07:18.250
He's going to be --
everybody's going

00:07:18.250 --> 00:07:24.070
to be celebrating his
100th anniversary in --

00:07:24.070 --> 00:07:25.400
starting at the end
of this year,

00:07:25.400 --> 00:07:27.550
but next year, particularly.

00:07:27.550 --> 00:07:29.680
And so we have his collection.

00:07:29.680 --> 00:07:35.130
So you could see music in
his hand here, and also,

00:07:35.130 --> 00:07:36.890
we have Oliver Smith's
collection.

00:07:36.890 --> 00:07:42.940
Oliver Smith was -- this
is from "On The Town."

00:07:42.940 --> 00:07:49.540
This is -- we have his original
drawings of sets, and this is --

00:07:49.540 --> 00:07:52.210
I mean, when -- might be more
fun to be here right now.

00:07:52.210 --> 00:07:55.710
This is the -- it looks like
it's Coney Island, right?

00:07:55.710 --> 00:08:00.590
So anyway, we have
things that link,

00:08:00.590 --> 00:08:03.450
and that shows people how
you can use original source

00:08:03.450 --> 00:08:08.320
material, and get ideas
about other things.

00:08:08.320 --> 00:08:12.760
The archive of folk culture
is the largest repository

00:08:12.760 --> 00:08:16.090
of traditional cultural
documentation,

00:08:16.090 --> 00:08:18.650
and one of the largest
in the world.

00:08:18.650 --> 00:08:22.000
It contains the largest
collection

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:26.830
of American Indian
music and spoken word,

00:08:26.830 --> 00:08:31.890
and the earliest ethnographic
field recordings made anywhere

00:08:31.890 --> 00:08:33.660
in the world.

00:08:33.660 --> 00:08:37.600
Veterans history collects
the stories of veterans,

00:08:37.600 --> 00:08:42.650
and to date, more than
100,000 of them are here.

00:08:42.650 --> 00:08:47.280
The Story Corps Project is a
nationwide grassroots initiative

00:08:47.280 --> 00:08:51.020
to record the oral
histories of people like you

00:08:51.020 --> 00:08:53.590
and me, ordinary citizens.

00:08:53.590 --> 00:08:56.160
How many stories
are probably buried

00:08:56.160 --> 00:08:59.880
in the Story Corps archives?

00:08:59.880 --> 00:09:05.490
I just -- since 1931, the
Library has provided books

00:09:05.490 --> 00:09:10.170
to the blind in Braille,
and now on sound recordings,

00:09:10.170 --> 00:09:13.590
the talking books and
digital playback equipment.

00:09:13.590 --> 00:09:15.850
And we have the world's
largest collection

00:09:15.850 --> 00:09:20.670
of cartographic materials,
more than 5-1/2 million items.

00:09:20.670 --> 00:09:24.400
And one of the really
interesting parts of that is,

00:09:24.400 --> 00:09:28.270
it's got the largest collection
of fire insurance maps of cities

00:09:28.270 --> 00:09:30.570
and towns in the United States,

00:09:30.570 --> 00:09:33.740
and they are amazing
just to look at them.

00:09:33.740 --> 00:09:36.780
They're very easy --
they're big-enough scale

00:09:36.780 --> 00:09:38.080
so that they're easy to read.

00:09:38.080 --> 00:09:42.510
You can go back and see where
your grandfather was, you know,

00:09:42.510 --> 00:09:44.380
born, and lived, and
that kind of thing.

00:09:44.380 --> 00:09:46.560
It's just very interesting.

00:09:46.560 --> 00:09:50.320
So basically, you can kind of
tell that I'm pretty much in awe

00:09:50.320 --> 00:09:53.080
of the embarrassment of
riches that we have here.

00:09:53.080 --> 00:09:55.450
And the only thing that
is disappointing is

00:09:55.450 --> 00:09:56.900
that it's not used enough.

00:09:56.900 --> 00:10:02.620
So I'm encouraging all of you
to think about that as you go

00:10:02.620 --> 00:10:08.790
about your own studies,
and creations,

00:10:08.790 --> 00:10:10.670
and also as you encourage
the people

00:10:10.670 --> 00:10:13.300
that you serve to do the same.

00:10:13.300 --> 00:10:16.090
And now, it is my pleasure

00:10:16.090 --> 00:10:20.090
to introduce Rhona Wolfe
Friedman, from the commission.

00:10:20.090 --> 00:10:22.820
Her passion for the
promotion of the arts

00:10:22.820 --> 00:10:27.770
and humanities is the reason why
this symposium has come about.

00:10:27.770 --> 00:10:29.800
And if you know Rhona, you know

00:10:29.800 --> 00:10:33.690
that she's a very difficult
person to say no to.

00:10:33.690 --> 00:10:36.160
And she will throw herself

00:10:36.160 --> 00:10:40.330
into producing the best
possible program to motivate you

00:10:40.330 --> 00:10:42.520
to go out and do good.

00:10:42.520 --> 00:10:46.600
So get ready for a
wonderful experience,

00:10:46.600 --> 00:10:47.900
because Rhona planned it.

00:10:47.900 --> 00:10:49.700
Rhona?

00:10:49.700 --> 00:10:57.600
[ Applause ]

00:10:57.600 --> 00:10:58.900
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman:
Good morning.

00:10:58.900 --> 00:11:01.060
It's wonderful to be here
in the Montpelier Room

00:11:01.060 --> 00:11:03.890
on the sixth floor at
the Library of Congress.

00:11:03.890 --> 00:11:06.870
The commission is delighted
to partner with the Library

00:11:06.870 --> 00:11:09.690
to present this arts
education symposium.

00:11:09.690 --> 00:11:12.710
The symposium would not
have happened, though,

00:11:12.710 --> 00:11:15.780
without the vision and
efforts of Susan Vita,

00:11:15.780 --> 00:11:17.240
the woman you just heard,

00:11:17.240 --> 00:11:21.310
the Chief of the Library's Music
Division, and Lee Ann Potter,

00:11:21.310 --> 00:11:22.980
sitting up front, the Director

00:11:22.980 --> 00:11:25.760
of Educational Outreach
for the Library.

00:11:25.760 --> 00:11:28.180
Lee Ann worked diligently
for months

00:11:28.180 --> 00:11:30.930
to make sure this
symposium would take place.

00:11:30.930 --> 00:11:32.730
Thank you to both.

00:11:32.730 --> 00:11:37.810
[ Applause ]

00:11:37.810 --> 00:11:42.730
And a special thank-you to
commission staff, Jeffrey Scott

00:11:42.730 --> 00:11:45.170
and David Markey,
who were great help

00:11:45.170 --> 00:11:48.260
with organization and logistics.

00:11:48.260 --> 00:11:50.880
I'd also like to
recognize Arthur Espinoza,

00:11:50.880 --> 00:11:54.010
our executive director,
and Kay Kendall,

00:11:54.010 --> 00:11:55.880
the chair of our commission.

00:11:55.880 --> 00:11:59.390
I'm now honored to
introduce Jane Chu.

00:11:59.390 --> 00:12:03.760
Jane Chu is the Chairman of the
National Endowment for the Arts.

00:12:03.760 --> 00:12:07.820
She has a background in arts
administration, philanthropy,

00:12:07.820 --> 00:12:11.910
and is an accomplished
artist and musician.

00:12:11.910 --> 00:12:15.400
Jane is the daughter of Chinese
immigrants, born in Oklahoma

00:12:15.400 --> 00:12:17.220
and raised in Arkansas.

00:12:17.220 --> 00:12:19.460
She's a pianist with
undergraduate

00:12:19.460 --> 00:12:23.240
and graduate degrees
in music and piano.

00:12:23.240 --> 00:12:25.630
Ms. Chu also holds
a master's degree

00:12:25.630 --> 00:12:28.630
in business administration,
a Ph.D.,

00:12:28.630 --> 00:12:31.300
and three honorary degrees.

00:12:31.300 --> 00:12:34.590
She has vast experience
in arts education,

00:12:34.590 --> 00:12:36.500
and arts administration.

00:12:36.500 --> 00:12:40.350
Prior to coming to the NEA,
Ms. Chu served as the president

00:12:40.350 --> 00:12:44.390
and CEO of the Kaufmann
Center for the Performing Arts

00:12:44.390 --> 00:12:46.440
in Kansas City, Missouri.

00:12:46.440 --> 00:12:50.620
At the NEA, under
Ms. Chu's guidance,

00:12:50.620 --> 00:12:56.280
the NEA has awarded more
than $377 million in grants

00:12:56.280 --> 00:13:00.760
to nonprofit organizations
and artists.

00:13:00.760 --> 00:13:05.730
Also, Ms. Chu launched the
United States of Arts Project

00:13:05.730 --> 00:13:08.420
that demonstrates the
importance of the arts

00:13:08.420 --> 00:13:10.980
in our communities and lives.

00:13:10.980 --> 00:13:15.920
In 2015, Ms. Chu launched
her signature initiative,

00:13:15.920 --> 00:13:20.900
Creativity Connects, to
investigate the current state

00:13:20.900 --> 00:13:25.550
of the arts in our nation, and
explore how the arts connect

00:13:25.550 --> 00:13:28.050
with other industries.

00:13:28.050 --> 00:13:31.030
It is no wonder that under
Ms. Chu's leadership,

00:13:31.030 --> 00:13:36.350
the NEA ranks first among small
agencies for the best places

00:13:36.350 --> 00:13:40.230
to work in the federal
government in 2016.

00:13:40.230 --> 00:13:44.510
With great honor and
pleasure, I welcome Jane Chu.

00:13:44.510 --> 00:13:47.990
[ Applause ]

00:13:47.990 --> 00:13:50.290
&gt;&gt; Jane Chu: Thank you so much.

00:13:50.290 --> 00:13:51.590
It's really wonderful
to be here.

00:13:51.590 --> 00:13:53.810
Thank you, and I want to
thank the Library of Congress

00:13:53.810 --> 00:13:56.550
and the D.C. Commission
on the Arts and Humanities

00:13:56.550 --> 00:13:59.050
for inviting me to speak today.

00:13:59.050 --> 00:14:02.880
Arts education is a topic
that's very dear to my heart,

00:14:02.880 --> 00:14:05.730
and it's not just because I
majored in music, or I majored

00:14:05.730 --> 00:14:09.930
in arts education, specifically
music education, in college.

00:14:09.930 --> 00:14:12.760
But it's because I have
known about the power

00:14:12.760 --> 00:14:15.560
of what the arts
can do for students,

00:14:15.560 --> 00:14:20.050
that not only honors the
appreciate of art, but it spills

00:14:20.050 --> 00:14:23.970
over into so many areas
of our daily lives.

00:14:23.970 --> 00:14:27.160
My father was a college
professor, not in music,

00:14:27.160 --> 00:14:30.820
but when he died when I was
nine, it was the piano lessons

00:14:30.820 --> 00:14:34.200
that I was taking as
a kid that soothed me.

00:14:34.200 --> 00:14:38.190
It was music that helped me
express myself beyond the use

00:14:38.190 --> 00:14:40.890
of just linear, everyday
conversations,

00:14:40.890 --> 00:14:45.460
and as a nine-year-old, I really
didn't have the full vocabulary

00:14:45.460 --> 00:14:49.080
to be able to express my grief
over the loss of a parent.

00:14:49.080 --> 00:14:51.980
And perhaps many
nine-year-olds don't have that.

00:14:51.980 --> 00:14:54.720
But I didn't have enough
words, since my parents,

00:14:54.720 --> 00:14:58.000
who were from China, spoke
Mandarin at home, and I,

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.580
who was born in Oklahoma
and grew up in Arkansas,

00:15:00.580 --> 00:15:02.630
spoke English at school.

00:15:02.630 --> 00:15:05.500
But the arts were there for me.

00:15:05.500 --> 00:15:08.900
So throughout my whole
growing-up years, I participated

00:15:08.900 --> 00:15:13.430
in as many arts activities as
I could find, from music camps,

00:15:13.430 --> 00:15:15.060
and singing in choirs,

00:15:15.060 --> 00:15:17.200
and acting in theater
productions,

00:15:17.200 --> 00:15:19.090
to drawing every day.

00:15:19.090 --> 00:15:23.240
And to this day, as an adult,
I still draw every day.

00:15:23.240 --> 00:15:26.240
So through my growing-up years,

00:15:26.240 --> 00:15:29.150
I became intellectually
interested in it, to the point

00:15:29.150 --> 00:15:31.330
where I majored in
music in college.

00:15:31.330 --> 00:15:36.620
So participating in the arts
gave me another vocabulary set.

00:15:36.620 --> 00:15:38.930
It's another language
that allowed me

00:15:38.930 --> 00:15:41.130
to express what I felt.

00:15:41.130 --> 00:15:43.440
Playing the piano soothed me.

00:15:43.440 --> 00:15:45.130
It became my refuge.

00:15:45.130 --> 00:15:49.530
Drawing allowed me to create,
and also live in the moment,

00:15:49.530 --> 00:15:52.520
where I was so immersed
in the creative process

00:15:52.520 --> 00:15:54.610
that time stood still.

00:15:54.610 --> 00:15:56.540
The arts helped me navigate

00:15:56.540 --> 00:16:01.880
through those bok choy corndog
moments, because I had the power

00:16:01.880 --> 00:16:06.260
to be able to make each
of us feel like we belong.

00:16:06.260 --> 00:16:09.740
That's what the arts do, even
when we're standing in the midst

00:16:09.740 --> 00:16:12.300
of living with multiple
perspectives,

00:16:12.300 --> 00:16:14.440
and different opinions.

00:16:14.440 --> 00:16:18.790
The arts give us tools
for self-expression

00:16:18.790 --> 00:16:21.690
when words alone are not enough.

00:16:21.690 --> 00:16:25.290
They help channel our
emotions, no matter how messy

00:16:25.290 --> 00:16:28.590
or confusing, into
something beautiful,

00:16:28.590 --> 00:16:30.780
rather than something
destructive.

00:16:30.780 --> 00:16:35.800
The arts help to empower us
to imagine new possibilities

00:16:35.800 --> 00:16:38.080
for what we might achieve.

00:16:38.080 --> 00:16:40.300
So everybody who
has participated

00:16:40.300 --> 00:16:43.620
in the arts has likely
experienced these effects,

00:16:43.620 --> 00:16:45.870
and all of you, I'm sure, have.

00:16:45.870 --> 00:16:49.950
But there is a growing body of
research about arts education

00:16:49.950 --> 00:16:53.360
that confirms what we
instinctively know,

00:16:53.360 --> 00:16:55.920
that children and
teenagers who participated

00:16:55.920 --> 00:16:59.780
in arts education
programs were associated

00:16:59.780 --> 00:17:04.340
with more positive academic and
social outcomes than students

00:17:04.340 --> 00:17:07.130
who did not participate
in those programs.

00:17:07.130 --> 00:17:10.750
And this was especially true for
youth who came from households

00:17:10.750 --> 00:17:14.610
with very few social or
economic opportunities.

00:17:14.610 --> 00:17:18.220
Eighth graders from
low socioeconomic homes

00:17:18.220 --> 00:17:19.570
who were active in the arts

00:17:19.570 --> 00:17:23.480
in elementary school showed
higher test scores in science

00:17:23.480 --> 00:17:27.240
and writing than students who
were not active in the arts.

00:17:27.240 --> 00:17:30.440
High schoolers from
low socioeconomic homes

00:17:30.440 --> 00:17:33.030
who were active in the
arts were more likely

00:17:33.030 --> 00:17:35.520
to complete a calculus
course than students

00:17:35.520 --> 00:17:38.150
with no arts-rich experiences.

00:17:38.150 --> 00:17:40.400
And across the board,

00:17:40.400 --> 00:17:43.820
arts-engaged students showed
higher overall grade point

00:17:43.820 --> 00:17:48.630
averages, and these higher GPAs
were found with all students

00:17:48.630 --> 00:17:49.980
who participated in the arts,

00:17:49.980 --> 00:17:52.330
regardless of where
students came from,

00:17:52.330 --> 00:17:55.350
regardless if they came
from low socioeconomic homes

00:17:55.350 --> 00:17:58.940
or high socioeconomic
homes, versus students

00:17:58.940 --> 00:18:01.390
who did not participate
in the arts.

00:18:01.390 --> 00:18:03.880
And high school students
who earned few

00:18:03.880 --> 00:18:06.830
to no arts credits
were associated

00:18:06.830 --> 00:18:11.180
with being five times more
likely not to have graduated

00:18:11.180 --> 00:18:14.150
than students who
earned many arts credits.

00:18:14.150 --> 00:18:17.790
The arts-rich students in high
school were more likely to go

00:18:17.790 --> 00:18:21.010
to college, more likely to
enroll in four-year colleges,

00:18:21.010 --> 00:18:23.120
more likely to get
a bachelor's degree,

00:18:23.120 --> 00:18:25.910
more likely to earn
mostly As in college,

00:18:25.910 --> 00:18:28.890
more likely to involve
themselves in the community.

00:18:28.890 --> 00:18:31.700
More likely to read the
newspaper at least once --

00:18:31.700 --> 00:18:35.430
or one time in the day,
more likely to participate

00:18:35.430 --> 00:18:39.750
in student government and
service clubs, volunteer, vote,

00:18:39.750 --> 00:18:44.080
especially those from low
socioeconomic backgrounds.

00:18:44.080 --> 00:18:46.120
And by the way, you can
find all of this research,

00:18:46.120 --> 00:18:48.900
along with hundreds of other
arts education studies,

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:54.740
online at artsedsearch.org,
and today, I'm drawing mostly

00:18:54.740 --> 00:18:57.060
from the work of
Dr. James Catterall.

00:18:57.060 --> 00:18:58.670
But you get the idea.

00:18:58.670 --> 00:19:01.710
There's a very strong
relationship between children

00:19:01.710 --> 00:19:05.080
and teens who have high
levels of arts engagement

00:19:05.080 --> 00:19:08.990
and positive outcomes for
their lives, versus those

00:19:08.990 --> 00:19:12.820
with low levels of arts
engagement, especially those

00:19:12.820 --> 00:19:16.600
who are challenged with fewer
social and economic resources.

00:19:16.600 --> 00:19:21.060
So what this means is that,
by closing the gaps in terms

00:19:21.060 --> 00:19:25.060
of who has access to arts
education and who does not,

00:19:25.060 --> 00:19:28.940
we're also helping to close
the broader achievement gaps

00:19:28.940 --> 00:19:30.990
that exist in our
educational system.

00:19:30.990 --> 00:19:34.770
So if we're serious about
evening the playing field

00:19:34.770 --> 00:19:38.640
for youth who come from low
socioeconomic households,

00:19:38.640 --> 00:19:40.270
then we need to get serious

00:19:40.270 --> 00:19:43.280
about providing equal
access to the arts.

00:19:43.280 --> 00:19:46.990
Because the arts are not a
matter of, it's nice to have,

00:19:46.990 --> 00:19:49.040
but only if there's
room in the budget.

00:19:49.040 --> 00:19:52.360
They are a necessity that's
going to help all children

00:19:52.360 --> 00:19:55.620
across the United States
reach their full potential

00:19:55.620 --> 00:19:59.710
in their every moments, and
for their successful futures.

00:19:59.710 --> 00:20:02.400
I know that the D.C.
Commission on the Arts

00:20:02.400 --> 00:20:04.320
and Humanities understands this,

00:20:04.320 --> 00:20:06.550
and I want to applaud
their efforts

00:20:06.550 --> 00:20:10.250
to bring the arts to
all D.C. students.

00:20:10.250 --> 00:20:12.850
Because the D.C. Commission
is one of the main supporters

00:20:12.850 --> 00:20:16.320
of the D.C. Arts and Humanities
Education Collaborative,

00:20:16.320 --> 00:20:18.590
and this Collaborative
is the newest member

00:20:18.590 --> 00:20:21.660
of the Kennedy Center's
Any Given Child Program.

00:20:21.660 --> 00:20:26.060
It's the first member to
span grades K through 12,

00:20:26.060 --> 00:20:30.880
to help communities expand
access to arts education,

00:20:30.880 --> 00:20:33.260
and we're really looking forward
to seeing the results here

00:20:33.260 --> 00:20:36.770
in Washington, D.C. Because
this program is going to work

00:20:36.770 --> 00:20:39.310
