00:37:34.130 --> 00:37:36.170
playing "William Tell Overture."

00:37:36.170 --> 00:37:41.850
I think it's played a -- I would
say a central role in my life,

00:37:41.850 --> 00:37:45.500
but what I want to say
a few words about now is

00:37:45.500 --> 00:37:47.470
that the research
over the last five

00:37:47.470 --> 00:37:51.100
to seven years has
actually provided evidence

00:37:51.100 --> 00:37:55.190
for the importance
of music education.

00:37:55.190 --> 00:37:59.160
And it's linked to success
throughout the lifetime

00:37:59.160 --> 00:38:01.910
of a person, and particularly
academic achievement.

00:38:01.910 --> 00:38:08.360
So there was a hypothesis put
forth by Dr. Aniruddh Patel

00:38:08.360 --> 00:38:11.210
from Tufts University, and
published in "Frontiers

00:38:11.210 --> 00:38:14.680
of Psychology" in 2011,
and it's easy to remember,

00:38:14.680 --> 00:38:18.420
because the acronym of
the hypothesis is OPERA.

00:38:18.420 --> 00:38:23.360
And that really, I think, sets
up a useful framework for some

00:38:23.360 --> 00:38:24.900
of the research that
has been done

00:38:24.900 --> 00:38:26.840
in the last five to six years.

00:38:26.840 --> 00:38:30.290
The OPERA hypothesis
proposes that benefits --

00:38:30.290 --> 00:38:34.640
possible benefits of music
are driven by plasticity

00:38:34.640 --> 00:38:37.770
in the speech processing
parts of the brain,

00:38:37.770 --> 00:38:40.050
and brain networks for speech.

00:38:40.050 --> 00:38:44.560
And this plasticity occurs
when five conditions are met,

00:38:44.560 --> 00:38:46.440
and so that's the acronym.

00:38:46.440 --> 00:38:51.490
And they are O for overlap, P
for precision, E for emotion,

00:38:51.490 --> 00:38:55.130
R for repetition,
and A for attention.

00:38:55.130 --> 00:38:58.130
There is anatomical overlap
in the brain networks

00:38:58.130 --> 00:39:03.820
that process sound features
used in both music and speech.

00:39:03.820 --> 00:39:06.210
For example, the amplitude
of the sound waves,

00:39:06.210 --> 00:39:10.600
as well as the periodicity with
which the sound waves appear.

00:39:10.600 --> 00:39:11.940
P stands for precision.

00:39:11.940 --> 00:39:16.680
Music places higher demands
on these shared networks

00:39:16.680 --> 00:39:20.870
when compared to speech
-- the demands of speech,

00:39:20.870 --> 00:39:25.240
in terms of how precise
the timing needs to be.

00:39:25.240 --> 00:39:27.450
E, for emotion -- the
musical activities

00:39:27.450 --> 00:39:31.320
that engage this network can
elicit very strong emotions.

00:39:31.320 --> 00:39:33.810
I don't know how many of
you have had the experience

00:39:33.810 --> 00:39:37.490
of feeling chills, or
shivers up and down your spine

00:39:37.490 --> 00:39:40.210
when you're listening to a
pleasurable piece of music.

00:39:40.210 --> 00:39:42.210
And of course, one
size does not fit all.

00:39:42.210 --> 00:39:44.850
It's very individual,
but we can agree that --

00:39:44.850 --> 00:39:46.590
and it's been scientifically
demonstrated

00:39:46.590 --> 00:39:48.220
in the last six years or so

00:39:48.220 --> 00:39:52.680
that powerful emotional
centers are activated

00:39:52.680 --> 00:39:54.270
when we're listening to music.

00:39:54.270 --> 00:39:56.130
R stands for repetition.

00:39:56.130 --> 00:39:59.670
The musical activities that
engage this network connected

00:39:59.670 --> 00:40:03.670
to speech are frequently
repeated as we're listening,

00:40:03.670 --> 00:40:06.640
and as we're practicing
an instrument or singing.

00:40:06.640 --> 00:40:09.340
And that repetition
is crucial to success.

00:40:09.340 --> 00:40:11.680
And finally, A for attention.

00:40:11.680 --> 00:40:14.210
Musical activities that
engage the network I'm talking

00:40:14.210 --> 00:40:16.410
about are associated
with focused attention,

00:40:16.410 --> 00:40:18.530
and of course, you
have to pay attention

00:40:18.530 --> 00:40:21.480
as we're learning a
musical instrument.

00:40:21.480 --> 00:40:23.130
So according to the
OPERA hypothesis,

00:40:23.130 --> 00:40:27.110
when these conditions
are met, neuroplasticity,

00:40:27.110 --> 00:40:31.220
long-term changes in the
brain drives these networks

00:40:31.220 --> 00:40:33.810
to function with higher
precision than is needed

00:40:33.810 --> 00:40:36.170
for ordinary speech
communication.

00:40:36.170 --> 00:40:40.860
However, since speech shares
these networks with music,

00:40:40.860 --> 00:40:43.530
speech benefits in
a secondary way,

00:40:43.530 --> 00:40:45.620
the processing of speech itself.

00:40:45.620 --> 00:40:48.130
And so the OPERA hypothesis
has been used to account

00:40:48.130 --> 00:40:50.920
for superior encoding of speech

00:40:50.920 --> 00:40:52.770
in musically-trained
individuals,

00:40:52.770 --> 00:40:56.670
which I won't have time to
go into in detail today,

00:40:56.670 --> 00:40:58.720
but I'm happy to
answer questions about.

00:40:58.720 --> 00:41:00.020
And this suggests mechanisms

00:41:00.020 --> 00:41:02.620
by which musical training
could improve the linguistic

00:41:02.620 --> 00:41:03.920
reading abilities.

00:41:03.920 --> 00:41:09.760
So I'm just going to run
through literally the headlines

00:41:09.760 --> 00:41:11.660
of studies published in
the last five, six years,

00:41:11.660 --> 00:41:15.170
and there's one particularly
relevant study by Nina Kraus

00:41:15.170 --> 00:41:16.780
from Northwestern
University in Chicago,

00:41:16.780 --> 00:41:19.110
which I think is inspiring,
that I want to focus

00:41:19.110 --> 00:41:20.410
on for a couple of minutes.

00:41:20.410 --> 00:41:25.260
So thus far, studies
have shown that babies --

00:41:25.260 --> 00:41:28.580
one-year-olds who have music
lessons with their parents tend

00:41:28.580 --> 00:41:32.680
to smile more and earlier,
and communicate better.

00:41:34.150 --> 00:41:37.610
Music training can improve
white matter connectivity.

00:41:37.610 --> 00:41:40.840
The highways in our brain
that connect the thinking,

00:41:40.840 --> 00:41:44.660
gray matter areas, and enable
rapid millisecond-level

00:41:44.660 --> 00:41:47.700
processing, they are
actually strengthened

00:41:47.700 --> 00:41:49.870
as a result of musical training.

00:41:49.870 --> 00:41:51.170
Not just listening.

00:41:51.170 --> 00:41:54.460
It needs to be active musical
training participation.

00:41:54.460 --> 00:41:56.420
So I could go into details
if you're interested,

00:41:56.420 --> 00:41:58.100
as far as how long it takes.

00:41:58.100 --> 00:42:03.410
It's not immediate, you know,
but after as little as one year,

00:42:03.410 --> 00:42:05.210
sometimes -- one
year to 15 months,

00:42:05.210 --> 00:42:08.020
the musical training changes
are seen in the brain.

00:42:08.020 --> 00:42:09.610
Where are the changes seen?

00:42:09.610 --> 00:42:10.910
Well, the corpus callosum,

00:42:10.910 --> 00:42:13.800
which is the main white matter
highway connecting the two

00:42:13.800 --> 00:42:16.310
hemispheres, the two
halves of the brain,

00:42:16.310 --> 00:42:20.110
that's actually made thicker,
strengthened as a result

00:42:20.110 --> 00:42:22.490
of musical training over time.

00:42:22.490 --> 00:42:27.030
And, the arcuate fasciculus,
which on the left side

00:42:27.030 --> 00:42:30.300
of the brain for most people,
serves as the main connection

00:42:30.300 --> 00:42:33.310
between the areas
understanding language

00:42:33.310 --> 00:42:37.320
and producing language
in the brain as well.

00:42:37.320 --> 00:42:39.100
Blood flow in the brain in some

00:42:39.100 --> 00:42:40.950
of those speech areas
I mentioned

00:42:40.950 --> 00:42:43.190
in the OPERA hypothesis
is increased,

00:42:43.190 --> 00:42:44.640
real-time practically,

00:42:44.640 --> 00:42:47.610
as a result of musical
training and exposure.

00:42:47.610 --> 00:42:51.340
Executive function, going from
point A, to point B, to point C,

00:42:51.340 --> 00:42:54.070
multi-tasking, so
crucial in our world --

00:42:54.070 --> 00:42:56.320
that actually improves
as a result

00:42:56.320 --> 00:42:58.140
of musical training over time.

00:42:58.140 --> 00:43:00.910
The gray matter -- not
just the white matter.

00:43:00.910 --> 00:43:04.200
Certain areas in the cortex,
the outer part of the brain,

00:43:04.200 --> 00:43:06.460
are actually made
bigger as a result

00:43:06.460 --> 00:43:09.260
of musical training
and exposure.

00:43:09.260 --> 00:43:13.530
Verbal memory and childhood
literacy is actually improved

00:43:13.530 --> 00:43:18.650
over time as a result of classes
exposing people to music.

00:43:18.650 --> 00:43:21.990
And this was not just for kids.

00:43:21.990 --> 00:43:25.100
Over the course of our
lifetime, as we age,

00:43:25.100 --> 00:43:27.950
there is now several
studies that show

00:43:27.950 --> 00:43:30.940
that the brain plasticity
is benefitted

00:43:30.940 --> 00:43:33.370
by musical training
throughout the lifetime.

00:43:33.370 --> 00:43:36.380
And in fact, this is now
beginning to be thought

00:43:36.380 --> 00:43:39.700
as a protective measure,
playing a musical instrument,

00:43:39.700 --> 00:43:43.140
against cognitive aging,
mild cognitive impairment,

00:43:43.140 --> 00:43:45.720
dementia of the Alzheimer's
type and others.

00:43:45.720 --> 00:43:48.590
But what I want to just
emphasize a little bit more --

00:43:48.590 --> 00:43:51.660
that's Dr. Nina Kraus's
work that I mentioned --

00:43:51.660 --> 00:43:54.270
is that it actually may --

00:43:54.270 --> 00:43:58.140
musical training in school may
actually help reduce academic

00:43:58.140 --> 00:43:59.540
achievement gaps.

00:43:59.540 --> 00:44:02.530
An August 2014 report from
the American Psychological

00:44:02.530 --> 00:44:06.240
Association stated that learning
