I -- you know, and there's a lot
of reasons why I don't want them

00:56:03.920 --> 00:56:05.220
out on the street at night.

00:56:05.220 --> 00:56:06.700
It's not necessarily
just for what they do.

00:56:06.700 --> 00:56:09.440
It's for what might
happen to them.

00:56:09.440 --> 00:56:11.870
So these are the challenges
that we're facing there.

00:56:11.870 --> 00:56:15.600
And how can we continue to
bridge our curriculum in ways

00:56:15.600 --> 00:56:19.090
that bring those different
socioeconomic groups together?

00:56:19.090 --> 00:56:22.020
I've anecdotally noticed in
our tuition-based program,

00:56:22.020 --> 00:56:25.530
which grew to be serving about
500 youth in the last two years

00:56:25.530 --> 00:56:28.140
from about 300 just
two years ago,

00:56:28.140 --> 00:56:32.080
that most of our tuition-based
programs racially look a certain

00:56:32.080 --> 00:56:34.560
way because of new
communities that have moved

00:56:34.560 --> 00:56:35.860
into that neighborhood.

00:56:35.860 --> 00:56:38.320
And our Youth Enrichment
programs racially look a

00:56:38.320 --> 00:56:39.620
different way.

00:56:39.620 --> 00:56:42.350
And so how do we curricularly
start to bridge that

00:56:42.350 --> 00:56:44.710
and create a foundation
for their futures

00:56:44.710 --> 00:56:48.350
that recognizes how incredibly
mixed our world is that we live

00:56:48.350 --> 00:56:52.170
in and provide tools
within which in one

00:56:52.170 --> 00:56:54.820
or two sentences they
can recognize the history

00:56:54.820 --> 00:56:57.780
of where we are, the
diversity in the room,

00:56:57.780 --> 00:57:02.990
and how hopefully we can
sense one another sensitively.

00:57:02.990 --> 00:57:04.790
&gt;&gt; Mario Rossero: Thank you.

00:57:04.790 --> 00:57:07.480
[ Applause ]

00:57:07.480 --> 00:57:10.310
Christopher, you make
me really think --

00:57:10.310 --> 00:57:12.580
I mean, I think this already,
but you, I think, articulated it

00:57:12.580 --> 00:57:17.200
in a very special way which
is, you know, arts education --

00:57:17.200 --> 00:57:20.330
I'm always a champion of working
from an asset model, right.

00:57:20.330 --> 00:57:22.840
And so the struggle -- instead
of like, "Oh, woe is me,

00:57:22.840 --> 00:57:24.140
the struggles that we have,"

00:57:24.140 --> 00:57:25.440
think about the power
that we have.

00:57:25.440 --> 00:57:28.960
And so I think uniquely
arts education,

00:57:28.960 --> 00:57:32.060
among other subjects -- we
think about literacy, math,

00:57:32.060 --> 00:57:36.160
etcetera -- arts education
is really so well-poised both

00:57:36.160 --> 00:57:40.310
out of necessity, but out of
its ability to not just be

00:57:40.310 --> 00:57:42.770
about curriculum and
instruction, right.

00:57:42.770 --> 00:57:46.520
Not just about what you learn
in the artform, but isn't it

00:57:46.520 --> 00:57:47.830
about listening, right?

00:57:47.830 --> 00:57:50.240
Isn't it about community?

00:57:50.240 --> 00:57:52.750
Isn't it about bringing
things together, right,

00:57:52.750 --> 00:57:55.530
recognizing past,
present, future?

00:57:55.530 --> 00:57:57.420
It has the ability to do
all these things and sort

00:57:57.420 --> 00:58:01.180
of knit them together in
a way that I think really,

00:58:01.180 --> 00:58:03.660
especially within a school,
within a neighborhood,

00:58:03.660 --> 00:58:07.600
within a program, it's got
this sort of superpower, right,

00:58:07.600 --> 00:58:09.750
this ability to bring
all these perspectives

00:58:09.750 --> 00:58:11.050
and things together.

00:58:11.050 --> 00:58:13.080
And I don't know that
everyone looks at the sort

00:58:13.080 --> 00:58:15.270
of other curricular
areas in the same way.

00:58:15.270 --> 00:58:17.560
So I appreciate your
articulation of that.

00:58:17.560 --> 00:58:21.010
So Nathan -- I've known
Nathan for a little while.

00:58:21.010 --> 00:58:23.930
We both were in Chicago Public
Schools fighting the good fight

00:58:23.930 --> 00:58:25.580
in arts education.

00:58:25.580 --> 00:58:27.440
I think we're the
two visual artists --

00:58:27.440 --> 00:58:28.740
&gt;&gt; Nathan Diamond: Yeah.

00:58:28.740 --> 00:58:30.040
&gt;&gt; Mario Rossero: -- up here.

00:58:30.040 --> 00:58:31.680
So Nathan leads the
charge in the team

00:58:31.680 --> 00:58:34.970
at D.C. Public Schools
for arts education.

00:58:34.970 --> 00:58:37.690
So I know you've got some
particular initiatives

00:58:37.690 --> 00:58:38.990
that we're going to dive into,

00:58:38.990 --> 00:58:41.750
but I thought you might
just take a moment to sort

00:58:41.750 --> 00:58:45.300
of continue the conversation and
talk about the work of equity

00:58:45.300 --> 00:58:48.910
and access in your role
and with your team,

00:58:48.910 --> 00:58:52.060
and then transition us
to your specific program.

00:58:52.060 --> 00:58:53.360
&gt;&gt; Nathan Diamond: Absolutely.

00:58:53.360 --> 00:58:56.630
So as Mario said, I'm
the Director of Arts

00:58:56.630 --> 00:58:57.930
for D.C. Public Schools.

00:58:57.930 --> 00:59:00.360
So in that role, I oversee
curriculum and instruction

00:59:00.360 --> 00:59:05.360
across the district and across
all disciplines in the arts.

00:59:05.360 --> 00:59:07.060
He also mentioned
I'm a visual artist.

00:59:07.060 --> 00:59:11.090
My background is in photography,
and design, and printmaking.

00:59:11.090 --> 00:59:14.090
But I am actually going to talk
about a music initiative today.

00:59:14.090 --> 00:59:15.390
And so that should be --

00:59:15.390 --> 00:59:16.690
&gt;&gt; Mario Rossero:
I'm just trying

00:59:16.690 --> 00:59:17.990
to represent all artforms.

00:59:17.990 --> 00:59:19.290
&gt;&gt; Nathan Diamond:
Absolutely, absolutely.

00:59:19.290 --> 00:59:22.140
And it -- you know, it's
been great to listen

00:59:22.140 --> 00:59:26.080
from Dr. Chu's remarks
all through about the idea

00:59:26.080 --> 00:59:28.700
of how we approach the
arts as a language.

00:59:28.700 --> 00:59:31.760
This is a real challenge,
I think, in education --

00:59:31.760 --> 00:59:33.860
in the education sector
because literacy has very

00:59:33.860 --> 00:59:35.230
specific connotations.

00:59:35.230 --> 00:59:40.030
And we are really pushing in
my office to broaden the scope

00:59:40.030 --> 00:59:42.780
of what we talk about when
we talk about literacy

00:59:42.780 --> 00:59:45.260
in public education, expanding

00:59:45.260 --> 00:59:48.480
that into visual literacy
and music literacy.

00:59:48.480 --> 00:59:53.650
And so the role, I think -- you
know, this idea of equity --

00:59:53.650 --> 00:59:55.060
these three words,
equity, access,

00:59:55.060 --> 00:59:57.790
innovation could not be
more kind of gift-wrapped

00:59:57.790 --> 01:00:00.570
for the work that
we're doing right now

01:00:00.570 --> 01:00:02.740
because Chancellor
Wilson, the new Chancellor

01:00:02.740 --> 01:00:07.300
of D.C. Public Schools, has a
really intense focus on equity

01:00:07.300 --> 01:00:11.940
and how we are approaching
our schools for what they need

01:00:11.940 --> 01:00:15.800
and what the communities need,
not just sort of even strokes.

01:00:15.800 --> 01:00:18.610
But what actually do we
need to give each student

01:00:18.610 --> 01:00:21.420
and each school so that young
people can be successful

01:00:21.420 --> 01:00:23.320
in D.C. Public Schools?

01:00:23.320 --> 01:00:29.690
And for us in the arts, that
comes in a few different forms.

01:00:29.690 --> 01:00:31.660
It's about exposure
and opportunity.

01:00:31.660 --> 01:00:33.690
And I think those are things
that sort of everybody

01:00:33.690 --> 01:00:36.770
in this room really
addresses quite frequently.

01:00:36.770 --> 01:00:38.670
But I think bigger
than that, what we look

01:00:38.670 --> 01:00:42.290
at is how are we empowering
students to use their voice?

01:00:42.290 --> 01:00:46.900
And so we talk a lot about
the use of a student's voice.

01:00:46.900 --> 01:00:51.470
And how do we transition from
a skills acquisition model

01:00:51.470 --> 01:00:53.790
where we area sort of
building students' capacity

01:00:53.790 --> 01:00:56.310
up to do certain things
as they get older?

01:00:56.310 --> 01:00:59.270
And more, how are we
handing them these tools,

01:00:59.270 --> 01:01:02.110
giving them space to use
them, to experiment with them,

01:01:02.110 --> 01:01:05.290
to understand them on their own
terms, and then guiding them

01:01:05.290 --> 01:01:06.840
from there as they get older?

01:01:06.840 --> 01:01:09.200
And so it is really about
how we are being strategic

01:01:09.200 --> 01:01:13.000
in that process from
pre-K through 12th grade.

01:01:13.000 --> 01:01:16.550
I think critical is, you know,

01:01:16.550 --> 01:01:18.960
literacy in the traditional
form is always

01:01:18.960 --> 01:01:20.740
about how do we get students
to express themselves?

01:01:20.740 --> 01:01:22.600
How can they write
their ideas down?

01:01:22.600 --> 01:01:23.900
How can they speak eloquently?

01:01:23.900 --> 01:01:27.260
How can we be sure that they
can sort of operate in society?

01:01:27.260 --> 01:01:31.810
But as we know, the arts
do that incredibly well,

01:01:31.810 --> 01:01:35.180
and they reach students who
are challenged to be reached

01:01:35.180 --> 01:01:37.830
by traditional forms
of literacy.

01:01:37.830 --> 01:01:42.620
And so one of the things
that we hold dear is

01:01:42.620 --> 01:01:46.880
that if we are not equitably
-- equity and access --

01:01:46.880 --> 01:01:49.310
if we are not equitably
reaching all of our students,

01:01:49.310 --> 01:01:51.520
there are voices
missing from our culture.

01:01:51.520 --> 01:01:54.150
There are voices
missing from our society.

01:01:54.150 --> 01:01:57.250
And if we know -- which we do --

01:01:57.250 --> 01:02:02.190
that a lot of the issues
of success in schools --

01:02:02.190 --> 01:02:03.760
as Christopher was
talking about,

01:02:03.760 --> 01:02:05.820
even in the way he
sees differences

01:02:05.820 --> 01:02:09.570
in his populations -- we know
there are a lot of things

01:02:09.570 --> 01:02:12.250
that fall along socioeconomic
lines.

01:02:12.250 --> 01:02:15.530
And so it is clear to us --
we can look at the research

01:02:15.530 --> 01:02:19.600
and know the groups of voices
that are actually missing

01:02:19.600 --> 01:02:21.790
from our culture that
aren't being expressed.

01:02:21.790 --> 01:02:25.320
And so to us the arts
is such a critical place

01:02:25.320 --> 01:02:27.710
where we have the potential
to start that change.

01:02:27.710 --> 01:02:31.880
And Dr. Chu spoke about
that eloquently earlier.

01:02:32.910 --> 01:02:37.630
So how we're doing this, we have
-- three years ago when I --

01:02:37.630 --> 01:02:39.880
three and a half years ago
when I came into this role,

01:02:39.880 --> 01:02:43.070
I was asked to really look
at what the curriculum

01:02:43.070 --> 01:02:46.950
of DCPS arts is and how
do we write a curriculum

01:02:46.950 --> 01:02:48.250
for the future?

01:02:48.250 --> 01:02:54.050
And so to Mario's point, the
arts don't live comfortably

01:02:54.050 --> 01:02:55.350
in the world of curriculum

01:02:55.350 --> 01:02:58.560
and instruction the way
traditional content areas do.

01:02:58.560 --> 01:03:01.990
This has a lot to do with
the way we evaluate and test.

01:03:01.990 --> 01:03:04.080
You guys know.

01:03:04.080 --> 01:03:05.380
&gt;&gt; Mario Rossero: Choir.

01:03:05.380 --> 01:03:06.680
&gt;&gt; Nathan Diamond: Yes, exactly.

01:03:06.680 --> 01:03:09.100
And so what we set about doing
was changing what a curriculum

01:03:09.100 --> 01:03:12.010
looks like, can it both meet
the needs of a district --

01:03:12.010 --> 01:03:14.720
can it look like what a
district needs it to look like,

01:03:14.720 --> 01:03:17.450
but also realistically
communicate what it is

01:03:17.450 --> 01:03:19.400
that actually happens
in an arts classroom?

01:03:19.400 --> 01:03:22.670
What value the arts add
to a student's life?

01:03:22.670 --> 01:03:25.010
And so we created what's called
the Framework for Arts Learning

01:03:25.010 --> 01:03:27.430
which is rooted in six themes.

01:03:27.430 --> 01:03:30.810
And those themes span
from pre-K through 12,

01:03:30.810 --> 01:03:32.780
and they are universal
themes that we

01:03:32.780 --> 01:03:36.590
as human beings explore
throughout our lives, identity,

01:03:36.590 --> 01:03:39.680
interaction, language,
determination,

01:03:39.680 --> 01:03:41.610
creation, and transformation.

01:03:41.610 --> 01:03:43.910
It is those six words
that anchor all

01:03:43.910 --> 01:03:45.430
of the work that we do.

01:03:45.430 --> 01:03:48.800
And the idea is that while
those are incredibly complex

01:03:48.800 --> 01:03:51.050
and deep things that
we all struggle

01:03:51.050 --> 01:03:54.730
with throughout our lives, if we
can start young people looking

01:03:54.730 --> 01:03:58.510
at those things developmentally
as a five-year-old

01:03:58.510 --> 01:04:00.320
that we are giving
them the opportunity

01:04:00.320 --> 01:04:03.100
to really explore what it means
to be human and what they would

01:04:03.100 --> 01:04:05.030
like to discover and understand.

01:04:05.030 --> 01:04:08.270
&gt;&gt; Can you say those again?

01:04:08.270 --> 01:04:12.610
&gt;&gt; Nathan Diamond: I certainly
can, identity, interaction,

01:04:12.610 --> 01:04:17.620
language, determination,
transformation --

01:04:17.620 --> 01:04:21.040
I'm sorry, creation,
and transformation.

01:04:21.040 --> 01:04:25.850
The tricky part about
this is those are --

01:04:25.850 --> 01:04:27.640
these are very lofty goals.

01:04:27.640 --> 01:04:31.930
And the question always comes
back to but how does that get

01:04:31.930 --> 01:04:33.570
to a student who
is five years old?

01:04:33.570 --> 01:04:35.480
Do we start talking to
them about transformation?

01:04:35.480 --> 01:04:40.080
And so I think what that
looks like then is we

01:04:40.080 --> 01:04:44.440
as the adults are putting
these sort of larger concepts

01:04:44.440 --> 01:04:47.440
of development at the
forefront of our planning,

01:04:47.440 --> 01:04:50.250
but that doesn't mean that we
aren't also bringing skills

01:04:50.250 --> 01:04:54.030
development and structure to a
young person to get them there.

01:04:54.030 --> 01:04:56.760
So it is really about how
we are being intentional

01:04:56.760 --> 01:05:00.380
that by the time a student
leaves D.C. Public Schools we

01:05:00.380 --> 01:05:02.560
want them to understand
what those concepts mean.

01:05:02.560 --> 01:05:04.020
But we don't start there.

01:05:04.020 --> 01:05:06.970
We start there in our thinking,
but not with young people.

01:05:06.970 --> 01:05:09.380
What it means for young
people is that when they are

01:05:09.380 --> 01:05:13.090
in an arts classroom, the
first thing they should feel is

01:05:13.090 --> 01:05:16.090
that what they are doing is
meaningful and matters to them,

01:05:16.090 --> 01:05:19.060
that it is connected to
their life, that they feel

01:05:19.060 --> 01:05:21.760
that they have a place
in what is happening.

01:05:21.760 --> 01:05:23.100
That's our entry point.

01:05:23.100 --> 01:05:26.300
We need to get them
engaged in what's going on.

01:05:26.300 --> 01:05:28.660
From there we can -- it's --
you know, when you have somebody

01:05:28.660 --> 01:05:32.490
who is engaged and ready to
learn, it is much easier to say,

01:05:32.490 --> 01:05:33.790
"Let's build some skills.

01:05:33.790 --> 01:05:35.930
Let's have some kind of
intentional instruction,"

01:05:35.930 --> 01:05:40.000
because now there's a
desire for that instruction.

01:05:40.000 --> 01:05:42.740
And then I think the most
critical thing that we infuse

01:05:42.740 --> 01:05:45.290
into every piece
of curricular work

01:05:45.290 --> 01:05:48.140
that we do is students
must have an opportunity --

01:05:48.140 --> 01:05:49.440
I call it playtime.

01:05:49.440 --> 01:05:50.850
Technically, I don't
call it playtime.

01:05:50.850 --> 01:05:52.300
That's what we call it.

01:05:52.300 --> 01:05:56.440
What I call it is like their
opportunity to experiment,

01:05:56.440 --> 01:06:00.280
to come to terms with the new
things that we are asking them

01:06:00.280 --> 01:06:02.100
to come to terms with before --

01:06:02.100 --> 01:06:03.920
this is the really
important part --

01:06:03.920 --> 01:06:07.080
before we decide to judge
them, before we assess them,

01:06:07.080 --> 01:06:10.280
before we grade them, before
we say, "This is high-stakes."

01:06:10.280 --> 01:06:12.660
We give them that space
to play so that we

01:06:12.660 --> 01:06:15.680
as educators can watch and
understand where they are,

01:06:15.680 --> 01:06:18.060
where their learning is, and
make sure that they have --

01:06:18.060 --> 01:06:19.360
back to that equity piece --

01:06:19.360 --> 01:06:22.150
they have what they need to
be successful as individuals.

01:06:22.150 --> 01:06:23.820
And then lastly,
I think they're --

01:06:23.820 --> 01:06:26.000
you know, in that
assessment role, in that time

01:06:26.000 --> 01:06:28.330
when we're really looking
at how far can you take this

01:06:28.330 --> 01:06:30.370
as a young person, we ask them

01:06:30.370 --> 01:06:32.650
to use those skills
in unique situations.

01:06:32.650 --> 01:06:36.200
We pose unique problems and
ask them to use those skills

01:06:36.200 --> 01:06:38.470
to solve those problems.

01:06:38.470 --> 01:06:39.940
So what this looks
like in practice --

01:06:39.940 --> 01:06:42.130
I said I was going to get to
an initiative about music,

01:06:42.130 --> 01:06:45.910
which I am -- is a program
that we launched at the start

01:06:45.910 --> 01:06:49.080
of this year called D.C. Keys.

01:06:49.080 --> 01:06:50.700
D.C. Keys.

01:06:50.700 --> 01:06:52.000
&gt;&gt; Keys?

01:06:52.000 --> 01:06:53.300
&gt;&gt; Nathan Diamond:
Keys, piano keys.

01:06:53.300 --> 01:06:57.370
And so this came from an
earlier idea that I had --

01:06:57.370 --> 01:07:00.530
that I was working on in Chicago
and then brought here was

01:07:00.530 --> 01:07:02.410
about a middle school initiative

01:07:02.410 --> 01:07:05.330
to begin ideas of
music production.

01:07:05.330 --> 01:07:08.540
How do we not just involve
kids in traditional ensembles,

01:07:08.540 --> 01:07:11.480
but how do we get them involved
in the idea of production

01:07:11.480 --> 01:07:12.780
and digital production.

01:07:12.780 --> 01:07:15.670
And how do we start to bridge
the relationships between what's

01:07:15.670 --> 01:07:19.480
in their headphones and what
happens in their music class?

01:07:19.480 --> 01:07:21.550
Which both in my role in
Chicago and my role here,

01:07:21.550 --> 01:07:22.910
there was a really
large disconnect

01:07:22.910 --> 01:07:24.210
between those two worlds.

01:07:24.210 --> 01:07:25.660
And so how do we start
to create bridges?

01:07:25.660 --> 01:07:29.060
And to me the first step in
that was starting to look

01:07:29.060 --> 01:07:31.070
at how the music that
they are listening

01:07:31.070 --> 01:07:32.370
to is actually produced.

01:07:32.370 --> 01:07:33.670
Like how do you start
to get involved

01:07:33.670 --> 01:07:36.260
in that creative process?

01:07:36.260 --> 01:07:37.840
It was an early process,
and a --

01:07:37.840 --> 01:07:41.080
like I said, it grew out
of something in Chicago,

01:07:41.080 --> 01:07:43.570
but it really --
I'm a visual artist.

01:07:43.570 --> 01:07:49.240
This is not my -- what I would
call my native discipline.

01:07:49.240 --> 01:07:53.620
And so it wasn't until two
years ago when I was hiring

01:07:53.620 --> 01:07:57.550
for a music position, and
ray Muller who's -- he's --

01:07:57.550 --> 01:08:01.130
I'm going to have somebody wave
to Ray Muller over there --

01:08:01.130 --> 01:08:03.360
who came in, and in
his interview the --

01:08:03.360 --> 01:08:06.200
what he said to me
changed everything.

01:08:06.200 --> 01:08:11.030
He said, "We need to teach
kids that music is a language.

01:08:11.030 --> 01:08:12.740
It is not something
to be repeated.

01:08:12.740 --> 01:08:14.640
And they are not just there

01:08:14.640 --> 01:08:16.780
to play something that's
already been written.

01:08:16.780 --> 01:08:19.390
It is there for them to write."

01:08:19.390 --> 01:08:20.880
And so I hired him.

01:08:20.880 --> 01:08:24.800
And then I was telling
him about this initiative

01:08:24.800 --> 01:08:27.230
that I had been working
on that was struggling --

01:08:27.230 --> 01:08:28.560
admittedly struggling.

01:08:28.560 --> 01:08:30.570
And he said, "Well, we shouldn't
start in middle school.

01:08:30.570 --> 01:08:31.950
We should start in
kindergarten."

01:08:31.950 --> 01:08:33.250
&gt;&gt; Yeah.

01:08:33.250 --> 01:08:34.550
&gt;&gt; Nathan Diamond:
And that was it.

01:08:34.550 --> 01:08:35.850
Like that -- you know,

01:08:35.850 --> 01:08:37.150
it was that instantaneous
[applause] -- absolutely.

01:08:37.150 --> 01:08:39.700
It solved so many
problems that I --

01:08:39.700 --> 01:08:41.000
you know, that I
was struggling with,

01:08:41.000 --> 01:08:43.220
but that I hadn't
identified which was, one,

01:08:43.220 --> 01:08:44.520
music will be a language.

01:08:44.520 --> 01:08:45.820
We'll just start it
from the beginning,

01:08:45.820 --> 01:08:47.120
so it will be no different.

01:08:47.120 --> 01:08:49.300
That's just how it
will always be taught.

01:08:49.300 --> 01:08:51.380
To how do we make sure that all

01:08:51.380 --> 01:08:53.330
of our students have
instrumental instruction

01:08:53.330 --> 01:08:55.780
which is incredibly
costly, and there's a reason

01:08:55.780 --> 01:08:58.920
that it often lives in high
socioeconomic neighborhoods.

01:08:58.920 --> 01:09:02.740
But in D.C. now we can say with
12 keyboards in every school

01:09:02.740 --> 01:09:04.400
which means the keyboards
that we have,

01:09:04.400 --> 01:09:07.110
24 students can be
playing at any one time.

01:09:07.110 --> 01:09:10.640
All of our elementary students,
25,000 kids, are learning

01:09:10.640 --> 01:09:13.160
to play the piano as we speak.

01:09:13.160 --> 01:09:14.460
&gt;&gt; Wow.

01:09:14.460 --> 01:09:19.460
&gt;&gt; [Applause] And so it solves
that issue of are we ensuring

01:09:19.460 --> 01:09:21.540
that our young people are
learning an instrument

01:09:21.540 --> 01:09:23.040
and learning to perform?

01:09:23.040 --> 01:09:26.930
And the last piece is
that it bridges the world

01:09:26.930 --> 01:09:28.230
of analog and digital.

01:09:28.230 --> 01:09:29.760
Right, it bridges
the traditional

01:09:29.760 --> 01:09:31.070
and the contemporary.

01:09:31.070 --> 01:09:34.430
The keyboard is the one
that both lives like a piano

01:09:34.430 --> 01:09:36.510
but can be plugged
into a computer.

01:09:36.510 --> 01:09:39.160
And so then we can
start this process,

01:09:39.160 --> 01:09:40.460
which the curriculum is rooted

01:09:40.460 --> 01:09:42.780
in composition and
improvisation.

01:09:42.780 --> 01:09:44.800
So our students,
starting in kindergarten,

01:09:44.800 --> 01:09:46.690
at the end of every
year will compose.

01:09:46.690 --> 01:09:52.170
You know, we need to shift our
ideas of what composition means,

01:09:52.170 --> 01:09:54.880
right, that it's a whole new
definition of composition.

01:09:54.880 --> 01:09:58.400
But we are asking them to use
music as a language every year

01:09:58.400 --> 01:10:00.610
that they are in
music education.

01:10:00.610 --> 01:10:05.580
The big headline of that, the
piece that matters most to me,

01:10:05.580 --> 01:10:09.470
is that as a system we
are creating young people

01:10:09.470 --> 01:10:13.170
who see themselves as
creative producers of culture,

01:10:13.170 --> 01:10:16.430
not just consumers of
culture, which is, I think,

01:10:16.430 --> 01:10:18.330
also a big shift in
what we're doing.

01:10:18.330 --> 01:10:21.950
We're not just trying to make an
audience for later on in life.

01:10:21.950 --> 01:10:23.250
We're actually trying
to make the people

01:10:23.250 --> 01:10:26.960
who create culture
later on in life.

01:10:26.960 --> 01:10:29.050
And we don't do this
on our own, either.

01:10:29.050 --> 01:10:31.000
I think critical
to this process is

01:10:31.000 --> 01:10:34.070
that we have worked very closely
with Washington Performing Arts,

01:10:34.070 --> 01:10:36.580
many of whom are here
in the audience today,

01:10:36.580 --> 01:10:41.570
as partners to engage kind of
the broader music community

01:10:41.570 --> 01:10:42.870
and to have access to things

01:10:42.870 --> 01:10:45.380
that as just a public school
system we don't have access to.

01:10:45.380 --> 01:10:48.060
And so they have supported
us in this process.

01:10:48.060 --> 01:10:49.910
They have worked
with our teachers.

01:10:49.910 --> 01:10:53.330
And they have stepped up to
say that they will be there

01:10:53.330 --> 01:10:56.080
when we figure out what it is
we actually need from them,

01:10:56.080 --> 01:10:57.590
which I think is
even more important.

01:10:57.590 --> 01:11:00.530
It's sort of like the blank
check side of it, which is like,

01:11:00.530 --> 01:11:03.120
"We are here for you, and
you know what it is that" --

01:11:03.120 --> 01:11:04.970
you just call.

01:11:04.970 --> 01:11:06.510
To the point where at --

01:11:06.510 --> 01:11:08.610
this year they have actually
changed their capital arts

01:11:08.610 --> 01:11:12.080
programs to meet the needs
of our new curriculum.

01:11:12.080 --> 01:11:14.850
With an organization that works
in so many of our schools,

01:11:14.850 --> 01:11:18.780
that's a critical relationship
that we have, that we can start

01:11:18.780 --> 01:11:22.720
to mold how the two
organizations work together.

01:11:22.720 --> 01:11:27.440
So to wrap up, I really
want you to hear this.

