01:21:57.420 --> 01:21:58.720
&gt;&gt; Asha Gardner: Okay, hi, guys.

01:21:58.720 --> 01:22:00.020
So I'm Asha Gardner.

01:22:00.020 --> 01:22:01.320
I do work with Split This Rock.

01:22:01.320 --> 01:22:03.650
I am a product of Split This
Rock nonprofit organization.

01:22:03.650 --> 01:22:07.370
For the past seven
years, since I was 15 --

01:22:07.370 --> 01:22:10.670
I'll let you guys do the
math yourselves, you know --

01:22:10.670 --> 01:22:15.130
I've been working in
arts programs with youth,

01:22:15.130 --> 01:22:19.940
worked all over the city with --
I don't know -- Split This Rock.

01:22:19.940 --> 01:22:22.050
I started off in high
school, you know.

01:22:22.050 --> 01:22:26.500
In high school, you
go to this wild place

01:22:26.500 --> 01:22:28.170
where it's like, "I
know what I think.

01:22:28.170 --> 01:22:29.470
I know what I want.

01:22:29.470 --> 01:22:30.890
I know what I need.

01:22:30.890 --> 01:22:32.980
And I have to voice it," right.

01:22:32.980 --> 01:22:37.920
But in schools there can be
a very definite structure

01:22:37.920 --> 01:22:40.210
as to how one can
present those needs,

01:22:40.210 --> 01:22:42.990
or how one can communicate
their feelings,

01:22:42.990 --> 01:22:45.200
or tell your teacher
what you went

01:22:45.200 --> 01:22:46.930
through at home the
other day, you know.

01:22:46.930 --> 01:22:49.470
And I felt for a while that --

01:22:49.470 --> 01:22:52.010
felt like there was
this like disconnect.

01:22:52.010 --> 01:22:53.760
You know, I felt like my
school had counselors.

01:22:53.760 --> 01:22:55.060
My school had deans of students.

01:22:55.060 --> 01:22:56.880
My school had vice principals.

01:22:56.880 --> 01:23:01.510
But there was no language
to use between us that would

01:23:01.510 --> 01:23:04.870
like effectively get my
point across, you know,

01:23:04.870 --> 01:23:08.220
to let them know that, you
know, "My heart hurts today.

01:23:08.220 --> 01:23:12.040
And I'm sorry I'm not paying
attention as much," you know.

01:23:12.040 --> 01:23:16.520
And I found a really great
sponsor in my building.

01:23:16.520 --> 01:23:19.380
She was actually the
librarian, that was as my mom,

01:23:19.380 --> 01:23:22.810
so that's why she was like the
best person in the building.

01:23:22.810 --> 01:23:25.780
But I kind of -- I found home
in the library, you know.

01:23:25.780 --> 01:23:28.450
And there was a space
where while I was sitting

01:23:28.450 --> 01:23:32.020
and like looking through all
these books and everything,

01:23:32.020 --> 01:23:35.610
this space where I could be
like, "I trust you, you know.

01:23:35.610 --> 01:23:37.430
You're an adult in this
building I can trust,

01:23:37.430 --> 01:23:41.470
like aside from the fact
that, you know, we're related.

01:23:41.470 --> 01:23:44.690
Could you please like, you
know, listen to me talk

01:23:44.690 --> 01:23:46.860
about the things I'm going
through just for a second?

01:23:46.860 --> 01:23:49.380
You know, with my
friends and other things?"

01:23:49.380 --> 01:23:51.340
You know, she would
listen to me all the time,

01:23:51.340 --> 01:23:53.220
but she would always in the
conversation be like, "You know,

01:23:53.220 --> 01:23:54.660
this is not what I'm here for.

01:23:54.660 --> 01:23:55.960
You know, I'm a librarian.

01:23:55.960 --> 01:23:58.170
You know, this is what
I'm supposed to be doing."

01:23:58.170 --> 01:24:01.850
And she challenged me one
day, and she was like, "Well,

01:24:01.850 --> 01:24:03.310
start a club, you know.

01:24:03.310 --> 01:24:05.840
You and all your friends come
here, and you sit around,

01:24:05.840 --> 01:24:09.080
and you talk about all your
problems, and you cry together,

01:24:09.080 --> 01:24:10.440
and you laugh together.

01:24:10.440 --> 01:24:12.990
So why not make it a
real club, you know?"

01:24:12.990 --> 01:24:16.370
And we were like, "Wow,
that's a really great concept.

01:24:16.370 --> 01:24:18.940
What kind of club can
we start to like talk

01:24:18.940 --> 01:24:20.460
about our emotions and things?"

01:24:20.460 --> 01:24:24.850
And you know, this
over -- I don't know --

01:24:24.850 --> 01:24:28.180
the spirit of art
was in the building

01:24:28.180 --> 01:24:31.240
because Split This Rock
was making their rounds,

01:24:31.240 --> 01:24:34.530
and opening up their new youth
programming with D.C. Slam Team,

01:24:34.530 --> 01:24:38.500
and bringing back all of their
big movements in the city.

01:24:38.500 --> 01:24:41.850
And she offered us this
opportunity to be like,

01:24:41.850 --> 01:24:44.040
"Start your own poetry
club," you know.

01:24:44.040 --> 01:24:46.920
And I was like, "What
are poetry clubs?"

01:24:46.920 --> 01:24:50.470
You know, I'm thinking like
Shakespeare, and Robert Frost,

01:24:50.470 --> 01:24:53.420
and like Emily Dickenson sitting
around together like, "Heh, heh,

01:24:53.420 --> 01:24:56.100
heh, this is so cool," you know.

01:24:56.100 --> 01:24:59.210
And I really like not,
you know, entertained.

01:24:59.210 --> 01:25:02.990
And honestly, it
didn't seem like a --

01:25:02.990 --> 01:25:04.630
you know, what we were
trying to get around to.

01:25:04.630 --> 01:25:06.230
It felt limiting, you know.

01:25:06.230 --> 01:25:07.530
&gt;&gt; Mario Rossero: Yes.

01:25:07.530 --> 01:25:08.830
&gt;&gt; Asha Gardner: And this idea

01:25:08.830 --> 01:25:10.130
of spoken word poetry
came about, right.

01:25:10.130 --> 01:25:12.700
And she brought these
artists to the building

01:25:12.700 --> 01:25:15.080
to present their program to us,

01:25:15.080 --> 01:25:16.500
to kind of like give
us a buy-in,

01:25:16.500 --> 01:25:18.790
like this is why you
should house our program.

01:25:18.790 --> 01:25:21.890
And there was an
artist, Rasheed Copeland.

01:25:21.890 --> 01:25:28.400
And he came in, and he did this
amazing poem about his sister.

01:25:28.400 --> 01:25:32.710
And I watched myself, my
friends -- we were theater kids,

01:25:32.710 --> 01:25:35.200
so you can -- we're a little
giggly and a little like,

01:25:35.200 --> 01:25:36.650
you know, we can't sit still.

01:25:36.650 --> 01:25:37.950
We can't help ourselves.

01:25:37.950 --> 01:25:39.660
And for that three minutes --

01:25:39.660 --> 01:25:42.650
his poem was no longer than
three minutes -- we were stuck.

01:25:42.650 --> 01:25:45.240
You know, we were
encapsulated in his world.

01:25:45.240 --> 01:25:47.220
We were feeling his emotions.

01:25:47.220 --> 01:25:50.400
We understood his
relationship with his sister

01:25:50.400 --> 01:25:52.010
by the end of the poem.

01:25:52.010 --> 01:25:55.210
And we sat around together --

01:25:55.210 --> 01:25:57.450
more so me, because I kind
of dragged all my friends

01:25:57.450 --> 01:25:58.750
into this poetry
club business --

01:25:58.750 --> 01:26:03.150
and we were kind of
like, "We can do this."

01:26:03.150 --> 01:26:06.970
And at the time in our
high school as, you know,

01:26:06.970 --> 01:26:10.370
minority students over in
Woodrow Wilson Senior High

01:26:10.370 --> 01:26:12.570
School, there wasn't
a big place for us

01:26:12.570 --> 01:26:14.290
in our musical theater program.

01:26:14.290 --> 01:26:17.060
It was unfortunate,
but we had --

01:26:17.060 --> 01:26:19.380
we felt like we had
all of this art in us

01:26:19.380 --> 01:26:20.680
and no place to put it out.

01:26:20.680 --> 01:26:23.610
And we were like, "Spoken
word sounds like nothing

01:26:23.610 --> 01:26:25.770
but monologues to me, you know.

01:26:25.770 --> 01:26:27.940
This sounds like something
I can do, you know."

01:26:27.940 --> 01:26:30.840
And personally, I was
jazz-trained in singing.

01:26:30.840 --> 01:26:32.760
A lot of my friends
were trained in singing.

01:26:32.760 --> 01:26:34.100
And we found all these places

01:26:34.100 --> 01:26:38.990
where all these different art
forms can meet in lyricism --

01:26:38.990 --> 01:26:40.320
simply lyricism, you know.

01:26:40.320 --> 01:26:42.450
Call it spoken word, call
it poetry, call it rap,

01:26:42.450 --> 01:26:44.060
call it what you may, you know.

01:26:44.060 --> 01:26:48.410
But it's this spoken form of
expression, you know, that says,

01:26:48.410 --> 01:26:51.250
"This is what I'm feeling, and
this is what it feels like.

01:26:51.250 --> 01:26:53.720
And let me let you feel
it, too," you know.

01:26:53.720 --> 01:26:58.510
So we started this poetry club,
and spoken word was our thing.

01:26:58.510 --> 01:27:01.020
We taught ourselves how
to do spoken word poetry,

01:27:01.020 --> 01:27:02.910
and we prided ourselves,
you know,

01:27:02.910 --> 01:27:04.650
in how far we had come with it.

01:27:04.650 --> 01:27:09.140
And this new era --
this new lane opened up.

01:27:09.140 --> 01:27:11.160
It went from spoken
word poetry --

01:27:11.160 --> 01:27:13.300
so we went from poetry
on the page, Shakespeare,

01:27:13.300 --> 01:27:17.070
all that good stuff, to like
this cool like modern twist

01:27:17.070 --> 01:27:19.850
on it, you know, more vocal,
more, you know, active,

01:27:19.850 --> 01:27:23.040
to this competitive part, right.

01:27:23.040 --> 01:27:24.750
Mind you, we're theater kids.

01:27:24.750 --> 01:27:26.050
We don't do sports.

01:27:26.050 --> 01:27:29.460
We don't have a sports team that
we can like fit into, you know.

01:27:29.460 --> 01:27:31.920
So we're like, "Competition,
you say?"

01:27:31.920 --> 01:27:36.490
You know, and so slam
poetry came into play.

01:27:36.490 --> 01:27:40.130
And what slam poetry is is
basically -- I don't know --

01:27:40.130 --> 01:27:44.440
individual students, groups
of students, teams, whatever,

01:27:44.440 --> 01:27:48.370
get together in a community
setting like an open mic,

01:27:48.370 --> 01:27:50.880
but instead of everyone just
going up onstage and just,

01:27:50.880 --> 01:27:55.230
you know, delivering their
emotions or their pieces,

01:27:55.230 --> 01:27:57.050
we add a little bit
of points to it.

01:27:57.050 --> 01:28:00.670
You know, we say how much
effort did you put into it?

01:28:00.670 --> 01:28:02.740
Did you really believe
the words that you said?

01:28:02.740 --> 01:28:04.710
Have I heard that poem before?

01:28:04.710 --> 01:28:07.220
You know, little -- all
these things start to matter,

01:28:07.220 --> 01:28:09.720
you know, and we start to
hold ourselves accountable

01:28:09.720 --> 01:28:12.910
for the artists that we're
building ourselves into.

01:28:12.910 --> 01:28:15.100
And we liked that challenge.

01:28:15.100 --> 01:28:16.400
You know, we felt
we had been waiting

01:28:16.400 --> 01:28:18.220
for that challenge
for a very long time.

01:28:18.220 --> 01:28:21.270
So Split This Rock started,

01:28:21.270 --> 01:28:24.430
the Louder Than a
Bomb DMV competition.

01:28:24.430 --> 01:28:26.440
Louder Than a Bomb was
actually a competition started

01:28:26.440 --> 01:28:30.730
out in Chicago amongst
Chicago city public schools.

01:28:30.730 --> 01:28:34.740
And it created this cool
place for all the kids

01:28:34.740 --> 01:28:37.330
from different areas
of the city, right.

01:28:37.330 --> 01:28:40.090
So if you can imagine, for D.C.
it would be something like --

01:28:40.090 --> 01:28:44.070
well, what it is something
like is people from Southeast,

01:28:44.070 --> 01:28:48.190
Northeast, Northwest, you
know, everyone coming together

01:28:48.190 --> 01:28:50.810
for a weekend -- one weekend.

01:28:50.810 --> 01:28:54.060
So every high school being
present, every demographic,

01:28:54.060 --> 01:28:58.440
every corner, ever thought
and belief, every walk of life

01:28:58.440 --> 01:29:00.660
from your city is
present, you know.

01:29:00.660 --> 01:29:02.680
And they're all in your
age range, you know.

01:29:02.680 --> 01:29:04.160
And you guys are
expressing yourselves,

01:29:04.160 --> 01:29:06.010
exchanging your thoughts,
and how --

01:29:06.010 --> 01:29:09.720
what your view is on your
life, you know, in the city.

01:29:09.720 --> 01:29:12.550
And you guys look around like,
"Wow, we're not so much --

01:29:12.550 --> 01:29:15.060
you know, we're not as different
as we thought we were."

01:29:15.060 --> 01:29:17.690
And we have elders --
I call them elders --

01:29:17.690 --> 01:29:18.990
the teachers, the sponsors.

01:29:18.990 --> 01:29:22.980
To be given that
term with respect

01:29:22.980 --> 01:29:25.980
because you guys
harness an environment.

01:29:25.980 --> 01:29:28.760
You guys are responsible for
this environment, you know,

01:29:28.760 --> 01:29:31.740
where students come, and
they are very vulnerable,

01:29:31.740 --> 01:29:35.260
and they are exposing a very
large part of themselves

01:29:35.260 --> 01:29:38.810
that in most cases if they
didn't have art would be silent,

01:29:38.810 --> 01:29:41.100
you know, would never be brought
to the surface, you know.

01:29:41.100 --> 01:29:43.800
And you guys are delegating,
you know, and helping them,

01:29:43.800 --> 01:29:46.850
and holding their hands,
and letting them know, "Hey,

01:29:46.850 --> 01:29:49.190
I saw a kid who did
a poem like yours.

01:29:49.190 --> 01:29:50.490
I think you might like them.

01:29:50.490 --> 01:29:51.790
Go check them out," you know.

01:29:51.790 --> 01:29:53.090
And look, there's a bond --

01:29:53.090 --> 01:29:54.880
a cross-town bond
started you know,

01:29:54.880 --> 01:29:57.470
turns into a friendship
that lasts forever.

01:29:57.470 --> 01:30:01.570
So kind of talk more on
what I feel like, you know,

01:30:01.570 --> 01:30:07.880
arts brings -- arts programming,
it's this opportunity, you know,

01:30:07.880 --> 01:30:11.830
for students to apply, to
challenge themselves, you know,

01:30:11.830 --> 01:30:17.610
to try community, you know, step
outside of their comfort zone,

01:30:17.610 --> 01:30:18.910
because I like to
think that a lot

01:30:18.910 --> 01:30:21.370
of times artists aren't
always the most --

01:30:21.370 --> 01:30:23.870
I don't want to say
normal people, you know.

01:30:23.870 --> 01:30:28.440
We aren't always -- we don't
always like fit in all the time.

01:30:28.440 --> 01:30:30.160
And that can be very --

01:30:30.160 --> 01:30:33.050
you know, it can put you
in a very isolated place.

01:30:33.050 --> 01:30:36.930
It can be socially
traumatic to a degree.

01:30:36.930 --> 01:30:40.730
Emotionally on the long term as
you build yourself into an adult

01:30:40.730 --> 01:30:44.810
and go down your line as --
to adulthood or whatever,

01:30:44.810 --> 01:30:47.540
you have all of these
issues, you know,

01:30:47.540 --> 01:30:50.390
because you never solved
your problems, you know.

01:30:50.390 --> 01:30:53.620
And we're having this
opportunity to start solving

01:30:53.620 --> 01:30:57.300
and addressing some of these
issues while they're fresh,

01:30:57.300 --> 01:30:58.600
you know, and they're young.

01:30:58.600 --> 01:31:01.630
And there are people, there are
sponsors, there are teachers,

01:31:01.630 --> 01:31:04.570
there are program directors,
there are teaching artists

01:31:04.570 --> 01:31:09.390
who are responsible for making
sure that that process goes

01:31:09.390 --> 01:31:12.720
as less rocky as
possible, you know.

01:31:12.720 --> 01:31:15.270
So what I do now is I
am a teaching artist

01:31:15.270 --> 01:31:16.570
in these schools.

01:31:16.570 --> 01:31:18.500
So I've gone through
the programs.

01:31:18.500 --> 01:31:22.950
I've done the slams, and
performing, and spoken word.

01:31:22.950 --> 01:31:26.570
And now I've seen the
opportunity to go back

01:31:26.570 --> 01:31:28.890
and teach, you know, my
students what I know.

01:31:28.890 --> 01:31:32.710
I felt like I made it -- I
got so many opportunities,

01:31:32.710 --> 01:31:35.250
and I made it so far
in my personal life

01:31:35.250 --> 01:31:41.120
by just expressing myself, you
know, by feeling these limits

01:31:41.120 --> 01:31:46.250
of -- and bounds just fall off
of me, that I felt the need.

01:31:46.250 --> 01:31:48.890
I don't know why.

01:31:48.890 --> 01:31:52.270
There's a student in D.C.
who isn't in a program.

01:31:52.270 --> 01:31:55.020
Honestly, on a realer note,

01:31:55.020 --> 01:31:58.050
I am from D.C. I'm
third-generation Washington,

01:31:58.050 --> 01:32:00.460
D.C., Washingtonian.

01:32:00.460 --> 01:32:03.880
And I've grown up with
students, with young people,

01:32:03.880 --> 01:32:06.180
with young adults from
all over this city,

01:32:06.180 --> 01:32:09.090
from all over the
country who do have --

01:32:09.090 --> 01:32:14.870
come from all areas of the
economic ladder, from all areas

01:32:14.870 --> 01:32:18.510
of religions, and walks of
life, all colors of skin.

01:32:18.510 --> 01:32:23.210
And regardless of
any of those things

01:32:23.210 --> 01:32:27.030
or how they differentiate, one
thing we all share in common is

01:32:27.030 --> 01:32:29.830
that it's critical
that we have something

01:32:29.830 --> 01:32:32.380
to do with our free time.

01:32:32.380 --> 01:32:34.430
So easy for us to
get in trouble.

01:32:34.430 --> 01:32:38.060
It's -- I mean, not kind
of like funny trouble.

01:32:38.060 --> 01:32:40.560
I mean, the kind of trouble
that doesn't allow us

01:32:40.560 --> 01:32:42.850
to come home ever
again, you know.

01:32:42.850 --> 01:32:47.880
And as a youth in the last
two years, I've had --

01:32:47.880 --> 01:32:52.530
I've lost friends, you know,
in the streets, and around,

01:32:52.530 --> 01:32:54.060
in front of their
homes, you know,

01:32:54.060 --> 01:32:55.470
in front of their neighborhoods.

01:32:55.470 --> 01:32:59.070
And I think to myself oftentimes
like if they had programs,

01:32:59.070 --> 01:33:02.240
you know, if they had a
sponsor, if they had a mentor,

01:33:02.240 --> 01:33:05.390
if they had somebody who
could keep their mind

01:33:05.390 --> 01:33:07.060
and keep them busy
on something else,

01:33:07.060 --> 01:33:09.140
would they still
be here, you know?

01:33:09.140 --> 01:33:11.020
And so I feel that's
the severity

01:33:11.020 --> 01:33:12.320
and that's like the demand.

01:33:12.320 --> 01:33:14.720
And that's what we do here.

01:33:14.720 --> 01:33:16.520
&gt;&gt; Mario Rossero:
Thank you for that.

01:33:16.520 --> 01:33:24.650
[ Applause ]

01:33:24.650 --> 01:33:28.290
I really love what you said
about the cross-town bond.

01:33:28.290 --> 01:33:30.290
So having spent 12 years
in Chicago, I know Louder

01:33:30.290 --> 01:33:31.950
Than a Bomb really well.

01:33:31.950 --> 01:33:34.390
And I just -- what I want
to paint for a picture

01:33:34.390 --> 01:33:36.720
for the room is if you
haven't been to one

01:33:36.720 --> 01:33:39.630
of these poetry slam
competitions,

01:33:39.630 --> 01:33:44.550
it is the most supportive house
of kids that you've ever found.

01:33:44.550 --> 01:33:48.680
Like I've been in auditoriums of
2000 high schoolers in Chicago

01:33:48.680 --> 01:33:53.190
from every neighborhood,
and they are only supportive

01:33:53.190 --> 01:33:57.010
of whoever is onstage, even
though it's a competition.

01:33:57.010 --> 01:33:58.880
And that's why I've
like adopted the --

01:33:58.880 --> 01:34:01.270
like I use the snap all the
time, because it's a way

01:34:01.270 --> 01:34:04.450
to show support when someone
is onstage struggling,

01:34:04.450 --> 01:34:08.240
but also sort of -- I don't
want to call it a milder round

01:34:08.240 --> 01:34:10.940
of applause, but it's
like a low hum of support

01:34:10.940 --> 01:34:12.730
that you can let people know
that you've got their back.

01:34:12.730 --> 01:34:14.190
&gt;&gt; Asha Gardner: Well, so
snaps are like a cool thing.

01:34:14.190 --> 01:34:16.260
So when you're -- someone is
onstage, and they're performing,

01:34:16.260 --> 01:34:19.430
right, and you get really moved,
because that's what we aim

01:34:19.430 --> 01:34:21.950
to do is like move you
guys out of your seats

01:34:21.950 --> 01:34:23.250
and like, "Oh, my God.

01:34:23.250 --> 01:34:24.550
That was great!"

01:34:24.550 --> 01:34:25.980
It's like -- it's kind
of disrespectful to step

01:34:25.980 --> 01:34:28.190
up in someone's home and
be like, "Oh, my God!

01:34:28.190 --> 01:34:29.490
That was so awesome!

01:34:29.490 --> 01:34:31.160
I"-- and they're still,
you know, talking.

01:34:31.160 --> 01:34:33.580
So we have this thing
in our communities.

01:34:33.580 --> 01:34:36.270
We have these little
mannerisms we do to --

01:34:36.270 --> 01:34:38.810
so we let people know that
like, "You are appreciated.

01:34:38.810 --> 01:34:40.110
You are being received.

01:34:40.110 --> 01:34:41.680
I am listening."

01:34:41.680 --> 01:34:44.190
So snapping is one thing
we do, you know, the snap.

01:34:44.190 --> 01:34:46.960
Another thing, if you're
ever in a poetry area,

01:34:46.960 --> 01:34:48.800
you can do like a
sweet chocolate noise.

01:34:48.800 --> 01:34:51.330
It's like if you have the last
piece of chocolate on the bar,

01:34:51.330 --> 01:34:53.600
you put it in your
mouth, you're like, "Mmm!

01:34:53.600 --> 01:34:56.480
Yeah." We like the sweet
chocolateness [sic].

01:34:56.480 --> 01:34:58.820
Also a new thing that the
community's adapted is

01:34:58.820 --> 01:35:00.260
awkward giraffe.

01:35:00.260 --> 01:35:02.310
So you can like throw your hand
in the air and be like, "Yes!"

01:35:02.310 --> 01:35:04.350
You know, little things.

01:35:04.350 --> 01:35:06.560
So there are these cool
little mannerisms we have

01:35:06.560 --> 01:35:09.220
in the arts community that
are teaching people how

01:35:09.220 --> 01:35:11.740
to like appreciate their
neighbors, you know,

01:35:11.740 --> 01:35:14.710
and how to respect, you
know, someone who's speaking.

01:35:14.710 --> 01:35:17.160
You know, all of these -- the
parts of -- I don't know --

01:35:17.160 --> 01:35:20.850
being a citizen, you know, being
humane in the world, you know.

01:35:20.850 --> 01:35:22.150
&gt;&gt; Mario Rossero:
Yeah, really lovely.

01:35:22.150 --> 01:35:23.950
Thank you.

01:35:23.950 --> 01:35:27.460
[ Applause ]

01:35:27.460 --> 01:35:29.380
Rhona, I think we
need to find some kind

01:35:29.380 --> 01:35:32.240
of cross-collaborative
project for us to work on,

01:35:32.240 --> 01:35:34.020
because these guys
are such rock stars,

01:35:34.020 --> 01:35:35.400
and I feel like we
could tackle anything.

01:35:35.400 --> 01:35:39.890
We're going to get to a
couple Q&amp;A in a moment.

01:35:39.890 --> 01:35:42.310
I just -- I'm going to start

01:35:42.310 --> 01:35:44.510
to once again knit
together this conversation,

01:35:44.510 --> 01:35:46.350
which I think is
already really connected.

01:35:46.350 --> 01:35:48.130
But you're hearing from, you
know, different perspectives

01:35:48.130 --> 01:35:53.340
about really the necessity of
the arts in everyone's lives.

01:35:53.340 --> 01:35:57.180
And I was thrilled
that Jane Chu talked

01:35:57.180 --> 01:35:59.770
about our Any Given Child
program here in D.C.

01:35:59.770 --> 01:36:02.500
that has really been
a work-in-progress

01:36:02.500 --> 01:36:04.160
for many, many years.

01:36:04.160 --> 01:36:08.160
We have a unique window of
opportunity for every sector

01:36:08.160 --> 01:36:10.480
of the community to
come together and say,

01:36:10.480 --> 01:36:14.800
"How do we prioritize
arts education in D.C.?"

01:36:14.800 --> 01:36:19.780
And part of the work to do that
is to look honestly at the data

01:36:19.780 --> 01:36:23.380
which -- and data
is a listening tour,

01:36:23.380 --> 01:36:24.960
hearing communities,
hearing voices.

01:36:24.960 --> 01:36:26.260
It's looking at numbers.

01:36:26.260 --> 01:36:29.610
It's looking at maps of the
city and analyzing the gaps

01:36:29.610 --> 01:36:30.910
and the saturation points.

01:36:30.910 --> 01:36:33.530
And it's also looking at
research and best practice.

01:36:33.530 --> 01:36:35.940
So it really kind of marries
these things together.

01:36:35.940 --> 01:36:38.660
So I would urge everyone to
kind of keep that on your radar

01:36:38.660 --> 01:36:42.740
and watch that progress,
because it's a real outcome.

01:36:42.740 --> 01:36:45.740
It's something that's happening
right now that takes this kind

01:36:45.740 --> 01:36:49.370
of conversation and puts it
into an actual structure.

01:36:49.370 --> 01:36:53.040
And I think, you know, if I add
anything to this conversation,

01:36:53.040 --> 01:36:56.030
you know, I get so
inspired, but I also laugh.

01:36:56.030 --> 01:36:57.460
When I worked in -- I've worked

01:36:57.460 --> 01:36:59.470
in school districts
my whole life, right.

01:36:59.470 --> 01:37:02.720
Well, when I worked at central
office, they mostly needed me

01:37:02.720 --> 01:37:05.940
to be the creative individual,
right, bringing a different kind

01:37:05.940 --> 01:37:08.010
of solution to a
problem, and then put

01:37:08.010 --> 01:37:09.700
that creativity into
a structure.

01:37:09.700 --> 01:37:11.570
But now at a performing
arts organization,

01:37:11.570 --> 01:37:12.960
they only need my structure.

01:37:12.960 --> 01:37:17.590
But for those of us that are
sort of the structure-heads

01:37:17.590 --> 01:37:20.930
in the house, that is
important, too, you know.

01:37:20.930 --> 01:37:24.310
When I hear Nathan talk,
when I hear Asha talk

01:37:24.310 --> 01:37:28.690
about the systems, the networks,
the role of mentors, that --

01:37:28.690 --> 01:37:31.560
the building of those
constructs is also an artform

01:37:31.560 --> 01:37:33.210
and really critical,
because you need all

01:37:33.210 --> 01:37:34.990
of us working in concert, right?

