01:37:58.170 --> 01:38:03.030
Thank you so much.

01:38:03.030 --> 01:38:04.420
Great.

01:38:04.420 --> 01:38:07.190
&gt;&gt; Hi, so first of all,
thank you, and especially

01:38:07.190 --> 01:38:11.280
to our youngest members of
the panel for your eloquence

01:38:11.280 --> 01:38:13.470
and for really walking the walk.

01:38:13.470 --> 01:38:14.770
Thank you for that.

01:38:14.770 --> 01:38:18.650
We've talked a great deal about
teachers, about institutions,

01:38:18.650 --> 01:38:19.980
about individual artists.

01:38:19.980 --> 01:38:22.640
But I would love to hear what --

01:38:22.640 --> 01:38:26.200
how you feel parents can be
more involved in the equation,

01:38:26.200 --> 01:38:29.610
because I think many of us who
have children or have children

01:38:29.610 --> 01:38:33.280
who are friends with children
in public schools, especially,

01:38:33.280 --> 01:38:35.730
wonder what their role is and
how they can be really active.

01:38:35.730 --> 01:38:38.240
And your mention of
your mom having this --

01:38:38.240 --> 01:38:41.830
these two roles sort of reminded
me to insert that question

01:38:41.830 --> 01:38:43.270
into the conversation.

01:38:43.270 --> 01:38:44.570
&gt;&gt; Mario Rossero:
Great, thank you.

01:38:44.570 --> 01:38:47.690
Who wants to tackle this one?

01:38:47.690 --> 01:38:50.120
&gt;&gt; Asha Gardner:
Well, I don't mind.

01:38:50.120 --> 01:38:55.600
Parents -- I think parents are a
necessary to all of the process,

01:38:55.600 --> 01:38:57.980
to -- that they bridge
the gap between the arts

01:38:57.980 --> 01:38:59.650
and the education, you know.

01:38:59.650 --> 01:39:01.130
They are the story.

01:39:01.130 --> 01:39:03.840
They are the emotion, the reason
that the kid is, you know,

01:39:03.840 --> 01:39:06.000
expressing themselves
in the first place.

01:39:06.000 --> 01:39:09.240
And I think the most
crucial part to that,

01:39:09.240 --> 01:39:13.130
which we lack frequently, is
presence of those parents.

01:39:13.130 --> 01:39:16.510
If you know your student
is involved in a program,

01:39:16.510 --> 01:39:20.930
urge yourself -- you know, urge
your student to be, you know,

01:39:20.930 --> 01:39:22.810
open to you being there.

01:39:22.810 --> 01:39:24.320
You know, show up.

01:39:24.320 --> 01:39:27.220
You know, leave them a note,
let them know that you're proud

01:39:27.220 --> 01:39:28.570
of them just for like, you know,

01:39:28.570 --> 01:39:30.290
preparing themselves
for the day.

01:39:30.290 --> 01:39:34.690
There's so many ways a parent
can put a foot, a hand,

01:39:34.690 --> 01:39:36.740
a finger, you know,
in the child's

01:39:36.740 --> 01:39:38.550
like developmental process.

01:39:38.550 --> 01:39:40.630
And it doesn't stop at home.

01:39:40.630 --> 01:39:44.250
It's a constant process until
they leave the nest, you know.

01:39:44.250 --> 01:39:51.570
And I think not just all along
the way, but with students --

01:39:51.570 --> 01:39:54.420
I'm sorry, teachers,
I think, it's --

01:39:54.420 --> 01:39:59.000
sometimes what we do is keep the
parents away from certain parts

01:39:59.000 --> 01:40:01.340
of the project because
it can be scary

01:40:01.340 --> 01:40:02.670
to have the parents around.

01:40:02.670 --> 01:40:04.070
You never know how
they're going to react.

01:40:04.070 --> 01:40:08.040
I've dealt with a few scary
parents already in my, you know,

01:40:08.040 --> 01:40:10.330
teaching years, you know.

01:40:10.330 --> 01:40:13.120
And I can, you know,
resonate with that.

01:40:13.120 --> 01:40:15.960
It can be very terrifying,
but you have to be open --

01:40:15.960 --> 01:40:17.260
&gt;&gt; Mario Rossero: That's right.

01:40:17.260 --> 01:40:18.560
&gt;&gt; Asha Gardner: -- you know,
because those are the people

01:40:18.560 --> 01:40:20.260
that made the student that you
love, and that you're watching,

01:40:20.260 --> 01:40:22.900
and who's watching
over you, you know, so.

01:40:22.900 --> 01:40:24.950
&gt;&gt; Mario Rossero: Yeah, I hear
really carving out that role

01:40:24.950 --> 01:40:26.250
and including them as well.

01:40:26.250 --> 01:40:27.550
&gt;&gt; Asha Gardner: Definitely.

01:40:27.550 --> 01:40:28.850
&gt;&gt; Mario Rossero: Yep,
you can add to it, Alex.

01:40:28.850 --> 01:40:30.150
&gt;&gt; Dr. Alexander Panteyat: I can
just share a personal example.

01:40:30.150 --> 01:40:33.680
I'm from the Ukraine and
started lessons at age seven,

01:40:33.680 --> 01:40:34.980
as I think I mentioned.

01:40:34.980 --> 01:40:38.680
And for the first five years
I took lessons, my grandma was

01:40:38.680 --> 01:40:40.800
in there every lesson writing

01:40:40.800 --> 01:40:43.000
in a red notebook
that I still have.

01:40:43.000 --> 01:40:44.300
&gt;&gt; Mario Rossero:
That's awesome!

01:40:44.300 --> 01:40:45.600
&gt;&gt; Dr. Alexander Panteyat: Very
large, hard-to-read handwriting,

01:40:45.600 --> 01:40:46.900
taking notes on what
the teacher said.

01:40:46.900 --> 01:40:49.230
And then I was required
to review it

01:40:49.230 --> 01:40:52.660
when I came home
and as I practiced.

01:40:52.660 --> 01:40:56.740
So that was definitively
formative for me, and --

01:40:56.740 --> 01:40:58.040
&gt;&gt; Mario Rossero: Oh, my God.

01:40:58.040 --> 01:40:59.340
That's beautiful.

01:40:59.340 --> 01:41:00.640
&gt;&gt; Dr. Alexander Panteyat:
-- feel very lucky.

01:41:00.640 --> 01:41:01.940
&gt;&gt; Mario Rossero: Okay, one
more response from the panel,

01:41:01.940 --> 01:41:03.800
