our next question.

01:41:03.800 --> 01:41:05.150
&gt;&gt; Christopher K. Martin:
I was just going to say,

01:41:05.150 --> 01:41:07.040
from an institutional
standpoint,

01:41:07.040 --> 01:41:08.840
what are the mechanisms
that we can put in place

01:41:08.840 --> 01:41:10.370
when it's difficult
for parents to show up?

01:41:10.370 --> 01:41:13.490
So how do we find
ways to support them?

01:41:13.490 --> 01:41:15.320
How do we sometimes
gently require it,

01:41:15.320 --> 01:41:18.220
because sometimes there
can also feel like arts --

01:41:18.220 --> 01:41:22.310
after-school arts programming
can start to feel like daycare.

01:41:22.310 --> 01:41:23.870
And there's a drop-off/pick-up
mentality.

01:41:23.870 --> 01:41:25.630
And so institutions
like public schools

01:41:25.630 --> 01:41:27.630
that often have sign-out
systems for young people

01:41:27.630 --> 01:41:30.630
because of protecting them,
can we institute that so

01:41:30.630 --> 01:41:33.230
that the parents have to come in
and, just as brief as that is,

01:41:33.230 --> 01:41:35.420
have that point of
contact and engagement?

01:41:35.420 --> 01:41:38.450
And then also when we start
looking at young people

01:41:38.450 --> 01:41:41.410
that become deeply invested
in their artistic practice

01:41:41.410 --> 01:41:44.030
and are considering
that for their futures,

01:41:44.030 --> 01:41:46.430
how do we support them in
the tough conversations

01:41:46.430 --> 01:41:48.760
with their parents that
sometimes are fearful

01:41:48.760 --> 01:41:50.600
of what a future in
the arts looks like?

01:41:50.600 --> 01:41:52.010
The future in the
arts looks like this.

01:41:52.010 --> 01:41:54.390
It's bright, and
beautiful, and supportive.

01:41:54.390 --> 01:41:56.770
It's not easy, but it's viable.

01:41:56.770 --> 01:41:58.550
And so I've -- totally
understand,

01:41:58.550 --> 01:42:01.180
my parents were not
sold on it for years.

01:42:01.180 --> 01:42:02.890
Even when I was making
money as an artist,

01:42:02.890 --> 01:42:04.460
they still were not sold on it.

01:42:04.460 --> 01:42:06.370
And if I had had advocates
that helped supported

01:42:06.370 --> 01:42:08.880
that conversation -- so we
as institutions can, I think,

01:42:08.880 --> 01:42:12.120
partner in a lot of ways
to help smooth that,

01:42:12.120 --> 01:42:13.610
as well as inviting
them in and trying

01:42:13.610 --> 01:42:15.530
to get them to be present.

01:42:15.530 --> 01:42:16.830
&gt;&gt; Mario Rossero: Thank you.

01:42:16.830 --> 01:42:18.130
&gt;&gt; Christopher K. Martin: Yeah.

01:42:18.130 --> 01:42:19.430
&gt;&gt; Mario Rossero: Great.

