01:53:37.090 --> 01:53:40.230
&gt;&gt; Lee Ann Potter:
Okay, hello again.

01:53:40.230 --> 01:53:42.090
You always hope that
after coffee

01:53:42.090 --> 01:53:43.770
and stretch time,
folks come back.

01:53:43.770 --> 01:53:45.360
So thank you for coming back.

01:53:45.360 --> 01:53:46.660
Appreciate it.

01:53:46.660 --> 01:53:48.170
So I'm Lee Ann Potter.

01:53:48.170 --> 01:53:52.040
I direct Educational Outreach
here at the Library of Congress.

01:53:52.040 --> 01:53:54.290
And a couple of months
ago when Rhona

01:53:54.290 --> 01:54:00.570
and I started brainstorming,
what this symposium would do --

01:54:00.570 --> 01:54:04.650
we agreed that it should answer
essentially four questions.

01:54:04.650 --> 01:54:06.170
Well, maybe three questions.

01:54:06.170 --> 01:54:07.870
I'll get to the fourth.

01:54:07.870 --> 01:54:09.970
We thought about why.

01:54:09.970 --> 01:54:11.500
We thought about how.

01:54:11.500 --> 01:54:12.800
We thought about what.

01:54:12.800 --> 01:54:14.230
We thought about all
those good questions.

01:54:14.230 --> 01:54:17.530
And as far as the why
goes, what we were thinking

01:54:17.530 --> 01:54:20.790
about was why Arts
Education matters.

01:54:20.790 --> 01:54:23.820
And I think our first panel
certainly did an excellent

01:54:23.820 --> 01:54:26.600
addressing the why.

01:54:26.600 --> 01:54:29.530
Our hope with regard to
the what was that some

01:54:29.530 --> 01:54:32.890
of you would be thinking,
"What does the Library

01:54:32.890 --> 01:54:34.920
of Congress have to do
with Arts Education?"

01:54:34.920 --> 01:54:37.490
It's not immediately
the first place we think

01:54:37.490 --> 01:54:39.280
of when we think of the arts.

01:54:39.280 --> 01:54:41.940
So our hope was that when
you had a chance to see some

01:54:41.940 --> 01:54:44.780
of the items from the
Library's collection and hear

01:54:44.780 --> 01:54:48.510
from Sue earlier about what else
is in the Library's collection

01:54:48.510 --> 01:54:51.720
that the what does the
Library of Congress have to do

01:54:51.720 --> 01:54:54.130
with Arts Education would
become much more clear.

01:54:54.130 --> 01:54:55.710
I hope that happened.

01:54:55.710 --> 01:54:57.890
By the way, did any of you
happen to see anything next door

01:54:57.890 --> 01:54:59.910
that you weren't
expecting to see?

01:54:59.910 --> 01:55:01.860
Good, that was kind of the hope

01:55:01.860 --> 01:55:05.870
that you'd see some things you
hadn't expected would be here.

01:55:05.870 --> 01:55:09.280
The next question is
really the question

01:55:09.280 --> 01:55:13.490
that our second panel is going
to focus on this morning.

01:55:13.490 --> 01:55:17.200
And that question is the how.

01:55:17.200 --> 01:55:21.000
So how do these amazing
resources that live

01:55:21.000 --> 01:55:23.710
in the collections of the
Library of Congress --

01:55:23.710 --> 01:55:27.830
how can they be incorporated
into Arts Education in ways

01:55:27.830 --> 01:55:31.630
that are truly meaningful
and truly inspiring?

01:55:31.630 --> 01:55:36.490
And so we have a marvelous
panel and I'm going to start

01:55:36.490 --> 01:55:39.670
by introducing you to
a colleague of mine.

01:55:39.670 --> 01:55:43.050
Ray White is a senior
music specialist

01:55:43.050 --> 01:55:45.050
in the Library's Music Division.

01:55:45.050 --> 01:55:47.840
And he is actually -- you know,
when I say that this is a panel,

01:55:47.840 --> 01:55:49.320
I got to be honest with you.

01:55:49.320 --> 01:55:53.190
It's really not so much a
panel as it is a performance,

01:55:53.190 --> 01:55:55.830
a panel and a performance.

01:55:55.830 --> 01:55:59.210
So our first performer
is my colleague Ray White

01:55:59.210 --> 01:56:02.270
and Ray is going to do
a performance for you

01:56:02.270 --> 01:56:06.790
that I hope will get you
thinking much the way a

01:56:06.790 --> 01:56:09.480
classroom teacher
is often thinking

01:56:09.480 --> 01:56:12.150
about how do we get young
people to understand

01:56:12.150 --> 01:56:14.160
that creativity doesn't
just happen,

01:56:14.160 --> 01:56:16.020
that it really is a process.

01:56:16.020 --> 01:56:19.800
And that rough drafts really
do play an important role

01:56:19.800 --> 01:56:21.320
in creativity.

01:56:21.320 --> 01:56:23.310
So with that, and that's all
I'm going to say about that.

01:56:23.310 --> 01:56:25.110
So Ray, it's your turn.

01:56:25.110 --> 01:56:31.170
[ Applause ]

01:56:31.170 --> 01:56:33.100
&gt;&gt; Raymond A. White:
Thank you very much.

01:56:33.100 --> 01:56:34.400
What I'm going to offer

01:56:34.400 --> 01:56:39.900
up in the next few minutes
are materials that are housed

01:56:39.900 --> 01:56:41.810
in the Library's Music Division.

01:56:41.810 --> 01:56:44.220
And they're among
our great treasures.

01:56:44.220 --> 01:56:49.360
And they do demonstrate the
creative process at work.

01:56:49.360 --> 01:56:54.290
Now, perhaps many of you may
be familiar with the song,

01:56:54.290 --> 01:56:57.000
"My Favorite Things" from
the <i>Sound of Music </i>.

01:56:57.000 --> 01:57:01.840
And perhaps the sound that runs
in your brain when you hear

01:57:01.840 --> 01:57:04.200
that is Julie Andrews
singing it.

01:57:04.200 --> 01:57:07.510
But suppose she sang this

01:57:07.510 --> 01:57:13.470
which Oscar Hammerstein wrote
before he wrote what you

01:57:13.470 --> 01:57:15.270
probably remember.

01:57:15.270 --> 01:57:44.510
[ Music ]

01:57:44.510 --> 01:57:48.040
[ Laughter ]

01:57:48.040 --> 01:57:51.270
Oscar Hammerstein was on
his way where he was going

01:57:51.270 --> 01:57:54.100
but he was not there
yet [laughter].

01:57:55.650 --> 01:58:01.600
Also from the same show,
there's the famous song called

01:58:01.600 --> 01:58:07.060
"Do Re Mi" and Oscar started out
with this idea that he was going

01:58:07.060 --> 01:58:11.090
to find some word to make each

01:58:11.090 --> 01:58:16.060
of those syllables
into a phrase.

01:58:16.060 --> 01:58:20.510
And this was before
he quite arrived.

01:58:20.510 --> 01:59:04.510
[ Music ]

01:59:04.510 --> 01:59:08.370
[ Laughter ]

01:59:08.370 --> 01:59:10.250
You sort of have
to figure out that

01:59:10.250 --> 01:59:13.860
when you get so -- it's sewing.

01:59:13.860 --> 01:59:15.160
We [inaudible] -- I don't know,

01:59:15.160 --> 01:59:20.000
who would necessarily
have thought of that.

01:59:20.000 --> 01:59:27.750
Now we shift gears to Irving
Berlin whose materials also

01:59:27.750 --> 01:59:29.310
reside here at the Library.

01:59:29.310 --> 01:59:33.510
And one of the things
that his materials for

01:59:33.510 --> 01:59:38.940
"God Bless America" demonstrate
that depending on the time

01:59:38.940 --> 01:59:43.610
and circumstances of
someone's creativity,

01:59:43.610 --> 01:59:46.000
their creative product may vary.

01:59:46.000 --> 01:59:48.380
Now the short story about
"God Bless America" is

01:59:48.380 --> 01:59:52.180
that it was originally written
during the closing months

01:59:52.180 --> 01:59:54.600
of World War I.

01:59:54.600 --> 01:59:58.170
It was part of an
all-soldiers revue called <i>Yip,</i>

01:59:58.170 --> 02:00:03.560
<i>Yip Yaphank </i>which was at Camp
Upton at Yaphank, Long Island.

02:00:03.560 --> 02:00:05.620
And this was going to be
the last song in the show.

02:00:05.620 --> 02:00:08.260
So he wrote this thing
called "God Bless America."

02:00:08.260 --> 02:00:15.960
Well, he ultimately decided
it was too anthem-like

02:00:15.960 --> 02:00:19.000
to be the end of this vaudeville
show so he put it aside

02:00:19.000 --> 02:00:23.130
and he came back to it
in 1938 and revised it

02:00:23.130 --> 02:00:26.150
when circumstances had changed.

02:00:26.150 --> 02:00:28.970
But this is what he first wrote.

02:00:33.510 --> 02:01:04.090
[ Music ]

02:01:04.090 --> 02:01:10.490
Now, okay in 1918, the
idea of left and right

02:01:10.490 --> 02:01:16.400
as political orientations
were not in common parlance.

02:01:16.400 --> 02:01:23.270
And all he meant was guide her
to the right path which is fine

02:01:23.270 --> 02:01:25.770
but guide her to the right
of the light from above.

02:01:25.770 --> 02:01:30.680
And then he decided 20 years
later when he was fixing it up,

02:01:30.680 --> 02:01:33.320
it became "Guide her through
the night with the light

02:01:33.320 --> 02:01:37.120
from above," which is just
plainly better poetry.

02:01:37.120 --> 02:01:41.700
So there went that change
but the song keeps on going.

02:01:41.700 --> 02:01:43.510
And it continues like this.

02:01:43.510 --> 02:01:55.040
[ Music ]

02:01:55.040 --> 02:01:58.500
Now, the part you were running

02:01:58.500 --> 02:02:00.940
in your head was probably the
mountains and the prairies

02:02:00.940 --> 02:02:02.930
and the oceans white with foam.

02:02:02.930 --> 02:02:05.670
Well, that didn't
exist in the early one.

02:02:05.670 --> 02:02:09.180
Make her victorious because
the United States was

02:02:09.180 --> 02:02:13.480
in a war at the time.

02:02:14.930 --> 02:02:21.430
But on land and foam [laughter]
-- foam has to rhyme with home.

02:02:21.430 --> 02:02:23.310
I get that part.

02:02:23.310 --> 02:02:28.700
But then he in 1938, went
back in the mountains

02:02:28.700 --> 02:02:30.800
and the prairies and the
oceans white with foam.

02:02:30.800 --> 02:02:35.250
Okay, that's an acceptable line.

02:02:35.250 --> 02:02:38.570
And -- but then -- so we
got the foam and the home

02:02:38.570 --> 02:02:42.610
and then he finishes
up with this end

02:02:42.610 --> 02:02:45.640
which I find a little
bit musically awkward,

02:02:45.640 --> 02:02:46.940
dare I say it.

02:02:46.940 --> 02:02:48.740
Ready?

02:02:48.740 --> 02:03:01.670
[ Music ]

02:03:01.670 --> 02:03:06.110
Now, I would say again, I
don't think there's anything

02:03:06.110 --> 02:03:10.450
at all wrong with writing
something that's clumsy

02:03:10.450 --> 02:03:14.760
or awkward or inelegant or
whatever you want to say

02:03:14.760 --> 02:03:17.590
in the creative process as long

02:03:17.590 --> 02:03:22.120
as the creative process
continues along [laughter].

02:03:22.120 --> 02:03:26.560
And it gets where it's
ultimately going to go

02:03:26.560 --> 02:03:28.260
which points out to me

02:03:28.260 --> 02:03:35.170
that music writing is
part art and part craft.

02:03:35.170 --> 02:03:38.060
And our last example is
also from Irving Berlin,

02:03:38.060 --> 02:03:43.210
his 1946 show, <i>Annie,
Get Your Gun </i>.

02:03:43.210 --> 02:03:45.920
Now if you met -- if you've ever
seen that show or know anything

02:03:45.920 --> 02:03:49.070
about it, you know it's
about Annie Oakley,

02:03:49.070 --> 02:03:54.220
the 19th century sharpshooter
and her friends Buffalo Bill

02:03:54.220 --> 02:03:56.970
and Charlie and Frank Butler
and they want to get her

02:03:56.970 --> 02:03:58.550
to join the Western Show.

02:03:58.550 --> 02:04:00.860
So these three guys sing this
song, "There's No Business

02:04:00.860 --> 02:04:05.690
Like Show Business" telling
her how great show business is.

02:04:05.690 --> 02:04:07.640
And so as the song goes on

02:04:07.640 --> 02:04:10.960
and the verses progress then
she kind of joins in with them.

02:04:10.960 --> 02:04:12.670
And then when they
get to the reprise,

02:04:12.670 --> 02:04:14.100
she sings it all herself,

02:04:14.100 --> 02:04:15.640
"There's no business
like show business.

02:04:15.640 --> 02:04:17.170
Let's go on with the show."

02:04:17.170 --> 02:04:22.640
Well, there were a lot of
words that Irving Berlin wrote

02:04:22.640 --> 02:04:27.300
for this song that didn't make
it to the final stage either.

02:04:27.300 --> 02:04:30.400
And bear in mind that the
ones that we're going to share

02:04:30.400 --> 02:04:33.070
with you now are
in that category.

02:04:33.070 --> 02:04:35.620
Before we do though, I would
like to introduce my colleague,

02:04:35.620 --> 02:04:37.760
Stephen Yusko, who has joined us

02:04:37.760 --> 02:04:39.380
at the piano for
this performance.

02:04:39.380 --> 02:04:41.180
Thank you, Steve.

02:04:41.180 --> 02:04:44.040
[ Applause ]

02:04:44.040 --> 02:04:47.390
So imagine, if you
will, these three guys

02:04:47.390 --> 02:04:49.850
and then Ethel Merman
belting out,

02:04:49.850 --> 02:04:51.650
"There's No Business
Like Show Business."

02:04:51.650 --> 02:06:32.510
[ Music ]

02:06:32.510 --> 02:06:39.040
[ Applause ]

02:06:39.040 --> 02:06:41.850
Thank you very much.

