&gt;&gt; Lee Ann Potter: Oh,
that was marvelous.

02:06:43.150 --> 02:06:44.450
Thank you, Ray.

02:06:44.450 --> 02:06:48.270
Terrific! So our
next two panelists

02:06:48.270 --> 02:06:50.320
and I'm going to
kind of this way.

02:06:50.320 --> 02:06:54.970
Our next two panelists represent
organizations that are part

02:06:54.970 --> 02:06:58.470
of the Teaching with
Primary Sources Consortium.

02:06:58.470 --> 02:06:59.770
And for more than 10 years,

02:06:59.770 --> 02:07:02.250
the Library of Congress has
been receiving appropriations

02:07:02.250 --> 02:07:07.070
from Congress that have been
directed to the Library for us

02:07:07.070 --> 02:07:10.360
to redistribute as
grants to organizations

02:07:10.360 --> 02:07:11.810
to develop curriculum

02:07:11.810 --> 02:07:13.970
and to make available
professional development

02:07:13.970 --> 02:07:16.440
opportunities for teachers.

02:07:16.440 --> 02:07:19.070
Today, we have 29
different organizations all

02:07:19.070 --> 02:07:21.510
around the United States who
are receiving grant funding

02:07:21.510 --> 02:07:23.720
from the Library with
all kinds of programs.

02:07:23.720 --> 02:07:27.810
Not all of them are specifically
connected to Arts Education

02:07:27.810 --> 02:07:32.200
but two of the programs that
are represented here today are.

02:07:32.200 --> 02:07:35.340
Erin Elman is going to
be our first speaker.

02:07:35.340 --> 02:07:39.410
And Erin is currently the
Dean of Continuing Studies

02:07:39.410 --> 02:07:41.770
at the University of the
Arts in Philadelphia.

02:07:41.770 --> 02:07:44.080
And I'm going to let
Erin take it from here.

02:07:44.080 --> 02:07:45.380
&gt;&gt; Erin Elman: Okay, oh.

