02:16:56.030 --> 02:16:59.420
So very briefly, this was a
course we developed last summer.

02:16:59.420 --> 02:17:02.690
So how many of you
have heard of STEAM?

02:17:02.690 --> 02:17:05.210
Okay, yeah, I got the
right audience here.

02:17:05.210 --> 02:17:08.060
So I don't have to
tell you what it is.

02:17:08.060 --> 02:17:13.250
So we decided to say, "Well,
what kind of STEAM objects,

02:17:13.250 --> 02:17:17.440
collateral art products are
available to the Library

02:17:17.440 --> 02:17:22.710
of Congress that can be tied
to all different disciplines?"

02:17:22.710 --> 02:17:24.340
And so we were so lucky.

02:17:24.340 --> 02:17:25.970
How many of you know
that the Library

02:17:25.970 --> 02:17:29.130
of Congress actually has
teachers in residence?

02:17:29.130 --> 02:17:30.430
See, they do.

02:17:30.430 --> 02:17:31.730
And they're great.

02:17:31.730 --> 02:17:33.830
And one of the past ones
is Trey Smith who was --

02:17:33.830 --> 02:17:35.800
he has a science focus.

02:17:35.800 --> 02:17:37.780
And I met him while I was
here at the Library for one

02:17:37.780 --> 02:17:39.080
of my consortium meetings.

02:17:39.080 --> 02:17:40.690
And I said, "Well, okay.

02:17:40.690 --> 02:17:41.990
We'll have to work with him."

02:17:41.990 --> 02:17:45.510
So he did a presentation
and it was wonderful.

02:17:45.510 --> 02:17:48.530
And he did some analysis
on and he really --

02:17:48.530 --> 02:17:49.960
even though he's a scientist,

02:17:49.960 --> 02:17:53.800
he was able to find
examples of STEAM objects.

02:17:53.800 --> 02:17:55.490
And then we invited in --

02:17:55.490 --> 02:17:58.770
we talked about teaching
artists today and so we invited

02:17:58.770 --> 02:18:01.370
in two teaching artists
who came in.

02:18:01.370 --> 02:18:02.670
One was Ben [Inaudible].

02:18:02.670 --> 02:18:04.660
You could see his
image on your left.

02:18:04.660 --> 02:18:06.500
I think that's right.

02:18:06.500 --> 02:18:11.980
Yup. He's a muralist but he
works with science and STEAM

02:18:11.980 --> 02:18:14.910
as motivation for
students kindergarten

02:18:14.910 --> 02:18:17.010
through 12th grade
to think about ideas.

02:18:17.010 --> 02:18:18.800
He's had exhibitions
in Washington, DC.

02:18:18.800 --> 02:18:20.190
He's worked with NASA.

02:18:20.190 --> 02:18:23.730
And he came in and talked about
his practice and his work.

02:18:23.730 --> 02:18:28.170
And then we also had another
teaching artist named Aster

02:18:28.170 --> 02:18:30.140
[Inaudible] who not only
talked about her work

02:18:30.140 --> 02:18:33.310
but she actually did a
project with teachers.

02:18:33.310 --> 02:18:35.290
And then we also
brought in an artist

