was working on.

02:38:05.590 --> 02:38:08.890
The first one is the
Explore the Building Cart

02:38:08.890 --> 02:38:11.230
which we had earlier.

02:38:11.230 --> 02:38:16.170
The Visitor Services
received this fantastic box

02:38:16.170 --> 02:38:17.890
of original materials
that we used

02:38:17.890 --> 02:38:20.190
in our construction
of the building.

02:38:20.190 --> 02:38:23.510
My colleague, Megan White and
I worked on this cart together.

02:38:23.510 --> 02:38:25.170
We went from researching
everything

02:38:25.170 --> 02:38:30.800
from how bricks were made to how
the pouring methods of granite

02:38:30.800 --> 02:38:33.660
and marble so that --
that way we could interact

02:38:33.660 --> 02:38:36.290
and have all the answers or
try to have some of the answers

02:38:36.290 --> 02:38:38.520
at least for our visitors.

02:38:38.520 --> 02:38:41.030
What is the Cart Program,
you might want to know.

02:38:41.030 --> 02:38:44.340
The Cart Program is a way for
visitors to come to the building

02:38:44.340 --> 02:38:46.760
and interact with us in
a totally different way

02:38:46.760 --> 02:38:50.700
where they can get hands
on, feel the original pieces

02:38:50.700 --> 02:38:53.220
of the building and
they can ask questions.

02:38:53.220 --> 02:38:54.520
A lot of times, people come up

02:38:54.520 --> 02:38:57.570
and tell me they were a
third-generation carver.

02:38:57.570 --> 02:38:59.700
They wanted to share
their experiences as well.

02:38:59.700 --> 02:39:02.730
So it's a really
fantastic experience.

02:39:02.730 --> 02:39:05.540
Docents are trained
on the cart material.

02:39:05.540 --> 02:39:07.530
They have gone through
a training program.

02:39:07.530 --> 02:39:11.650
They have a wonderful manual and
so we're there to support them.

02:39:11.650 --> 02:39:13.560
The other project that
I was lucky to work

02:39:13.560 --> 02:39:16.210
on this past year was
their Touch History Program

02:39:16.210 --> 02:39:20.460
which is our tour for the
blind and visually impaired.

02:39:20.460 --> 02:39:24.320
We at the Visitors Services
have fantastic tours.

02:39:24.320 --> 02:39:28.960
We offer constituent public
reserved tours throughout

02:39:28.960 --> 02:39:30.260
the day.

02:39:30.260 --> 02:39:33.830
Our docents go through
a 10-hours-a-week,

02:39:33.830 --> 02:39:37.520
15-week training program
for a total of 150 hours.

02:39:37.520 --> 02:39:39.000
And with that is just
to share with you

02:39:39.000 --> 02:39:43.050
that this is a well-developed,
well-researched tour.

02:39:43.050 --> 02:39:46.100
It's not just drawn
together quickly.

02:39:46.100 --> 02:39:49.350
The docents that are chosen

02:39:49.350 --> 02:39:53.030
to do Touch History have been
docents for at least one year.

02:39:53.030 --> 02:39:56.060
They are not completely
new to the program.

02:39:56.060 --> 02:40:00.040
The Touch History, we enhanced
verbally our normal tour.

02:40:00.040 --> 02:40:02.300
So we give great history.

02:40:02.300 --> 02:40:07.230
That's similar but then we go
into more descriptive ability

02:40:07.230 --> 02:40:09.240
with the building, give
people an opportunity.

02:40:09.240 --> 02:40:12.510
We also reached out to the
architect of the Capitol

02:40:12.510 --> 02:40:15.010
and let them know that we
were working on this project.

02:40:15.010 --> 02:40:17.070
And they were incredibly
generous with us.

02:40:17.070 --> 02:40:18.470
We have the best.

02:40:18.470 --> 02:40:19.920
And so many of you saw.

02:40:19.920 --> 02:40:21.850
I have an original brick here.

02:40:21.850 --> 02:40:23.200
A lot of people don't know

02:40:23.200 --> 02:40:25.620
that the Jefferson Building
really is a brick building --

02:40:25.620 --> 02:40:29.030
22 million bricks went to the
construction of this building.

02:40:29.030 --> 02:40:31.290
But you don't really see them
so people don't realize that.

02:40:31.290 --> 02:40:32.590
So I have a brick.

02:40:32.590 --> 02:40:33.890
You can feel it.

02:40:33.890 --> 02:40:35.190
It's quite heavy.

02:40:35.190 --> 02:40:38.640
The -- and also a piece of the
granite because the exterior

02:40:38.640 --> 02:40:41.120
of the building, we have
like a cross-section.

02:40:41.120 --> 02:40:43.130
So you have -- the
granite is on the exterior.

02:40:43.130 --> 02:40:45.810
We have the marble -- the
brick plaster and then,

02:40:45.810 --> 02:40:47.110
of course, the marble.

02:40:47.110 --> 02:40:48.410
If you've been in the building,

02:40:48.410 --> 02:40:49.830
you've seen that
we are a marble.

02:40:49.830 --> 02:40:53.570
That is just like the icing,
like the -- on the cake there.

02:40:53.570 --> 02:40:55.210
It's marble cladding.

02:40:55.210 --> 02:40:56.720
And this allows visitors

02:40:56.720 --> 02:40:58.020
when we're doing a
Touch History Tour,

02:40:58.020 --> 02:41:00.070
I can hand these
to our visitors.

02:41:00.070 --> 02:41:01.370
They can feel them.

02:41:01.370 --> 02:41:03.590
They can interact with
them, feel the coolness,

02:41:03.590 --> 02:41:05.760
the smoothness of the surface.

02:41:05.760 --> 02:41:09.350
Depending on their visual
ability, they can maybe want

02:41:09.350 --> 02:41:12.310
to reach up and look
at it closely.

02:41:12.310 --> 02:41:14.900
The tour allows that
for our visitors.

02:41:14.900 --> 02:41:20.420
The -- I want to back up a
little bit also because I want

02:41:20.420 --> 02:41:23.900
to talk a little bit
about the ceiling.

02:41:23.900 --> 02:41:25.530
The architecture of this
[inaudible] was fantastic.

02:41:25.530 --> 02:41:27.800
I have some original
pieces of the marble mosaics

02:41:27.800 --> 02:41:31.000
which I didn't bring over with
me on -- but the architect did.

02:41:31.000 --> 02:41:32.830
If you've been in our
building, you'd see three

02:41:32.830 --> 02:41:35.070
of our alcoves are
mosaic ceilings.

02:41:35.070 --> 02:41:38.960
And the architect put
them on a wooden base

02:41:38.960 --> 02:41:41.660
so that we can hand
these out when people --

02:41:41.660 --> 02:41:43.530
let our visitors feel this.

02:41:43.530 --> 02:41:48.110
Get a real sense of what this
-- the incredible artistic --

02:41:48.110 --> 02:41:50.750
artistry that was involved
in doing these ceilings.

02:41:50.750 --> 02:41:54.590
So that's just a little bit
about the why and how we did it.

02:41:54.590 --> 02:41:57.250
We also besides working
-- I researched.

02:41:57.250 --> 02:41:58.710
I went to a lot of museums

02:41:58.710 --> 02:42:00.230
to see what they were
doing throughout the --

02:42:00.230 --> 02:42:04.240
you know, in New York
and here in Washington.

02:42:04.240 --> 02:42:07.410
We researched online to see what
best practices are the museum

02:42:07.410 --> 02:42:09.850
world are doing in
tactile tours.

02:42:09.850 --> 02:42:14.550
Luckily, we have a fantastic
