02:42:14.550 --> 02:42:18.600
our equal opportunity disability
programs and we worked

02:42:18.600 --> 02:42:22.060
with Lorena Bradford from
the National Gallery of Art

02:42:22.060 --> 02:42:25.740
and had a wonderful
review with her.

02:42:25.740 --> 02:42:27.040
So let me tell you about --

02:42:27.040 --> 02:42:30.320
I told you that we
do a descriptive.

02:42:30.320 --> 02:42:35.780
So let me -- if I can,
this is going to be fun.

02:42:35.780 --> 02:42:37.480
Let me give you a
little bit of a tour

02:42:37.480 --> 02:42:38.780
of going into the building.

02:42:38.780 --> 02:42:42.360
If you've never been in our
building, this will be exciting.

02:42:42.360 --> 02:42:45.980
So the Jefferson -- the Library
of Congress was created --

02:42:45.980 --> 02:42:48.290
let's back up, 1800, correct?

02:42:48.290 --> 02:42:51.600
And our first 97 years
were spent in the Capitol.

02:42:51.600 --> 02:42:55.520
That's where we are -- we began.

02:42:55.520 --> 02:42:58.460
Then we are -- the
Librarian at that time wanted

02:42:58.460 --> 02:43:01.380
to see us expanding our services
and wanted a larger building.

02:43:01.380 --> 02:43:04.760
So they -- Congress
appropriated the funds

02:43:04.760 --> 02:43:06.400
to build the Jefferson Building.

02:43:06.400 --> 02:43:07.930
So let's talk about
the Jefferson Building.

02:43:07.930 --> 02:43:09.440
You walk up the grand staircase.

02:43:09.440 --> 02:43:12.320
You come into the building,
into the first alcove

02:43:12.320 --> 02:43:14.090
which is the Alcove of Minerva.

02:43:14.090 --> 02:43:15.980
Minerva -- there
are four alcoves

02:43:15.980 --> 02:43:17.390
that surround the great hall.

02:43:17.390 --> 02:43:18.910
The first one is Minerva.

02:43:18.910 --> 02:43:20.210
You walk in there.

02:43:20.210 --> 02:43:22.000
There are the eight
pairs of Minerva,

02:43:22.000 --> 02:43:25.630
goddess of wisdom
and defense of war.

02:43:25.630 --> 02:43:27.240
From there, we walk
through the arch --

02:43:27.240 --> 02:43:29.500
one of the three arches
into the Great Hall.

02:43:29.500 --> 02:43:32.370
The building is fantastic
in its symmetry.

02:43:32.370 --> 02:43:35.130
What's done on one side is
equally done on the opposite.

02:43:35.130 --> 02:43:37.640
If it's on the left, it
will be equal on the right.

02:43:37.640 --> 02:43:39.400
I love this building.

02:43:39.400 --> 02:43:41.220
So we're now standing
in the Great Hall.

02:43:41.220 --> 02:43:42.520
Let's align ourselves.

02:43:42.520 --> 02:43:43.820
We're in Great Hall.

02:43:43.820 --> 02:43:45.120
We hear lots of sounds.

02:43:45.120 --> 02:43:46.420
It's really noisy.

02:43:46.420 --> 02:43:48.820
The Great Hall is called that
because it's pretty large.

02:43:48.820 --> 02:43:52.710
It's 50 feet across and it's
about 43 feet from front

02:43:52.710 --> 02:43:55.080
to the next set of arches.

02:43:55.080 --> 02:43:57.590
It's 75 feet to the ceiling.

02:43:57.590 --> 02:43:58.890
So it's quite large.

02:43:58.890 --> 02:44:01.780
From where we're standing,
if we were to look up,

02:44:01.780 --> 02:44:03.690
we can see up to
the mezzanine level.

02:44:03.690 --> 02:44:07.160
And there is a marble
banister that runs all around.

02:44:07.160 --> 02:44:10.100
So this, the mezzanine
level is available

02:44:10.100 --> 02:44:11.400
to us, the sound of it.

02:44:11.400 --> 02:44:12.710
So it's quite loud.

02:44:12.710 --> 02:44:14.820
Right and on the left-hand
side of the Great Hall,

02:44:14.820 --> 02:44:16.530
we have the Grand Staircases.

02:44:16.530 --> 02:44:17.830
These are fantastic.

02:44:17.830 --> 02:44:20.080
They're about nine feet wide.

02:44:20.080 --> 02:44:22.380
There's -- they go up
to the second level.

02:44:22.380 --> 02:44:25.410
And of course, on the
sides of the staircase,

02:44:25.410 --> 02:44:26.720
they could have left them plain.

02:44:26.720 --> 02:44:28.140
But why would we do that?

02:44:28.140 --> 02:44:29.990
This is 1897.

02:44:29.990 --> 02:44:31.850
Why did we want to do that?

02:44:31.850 --> 02:44:35.340
So we have these fantastic
sculptures going up the sides

02:44:35.340 --> 02:44:36.780
and they are called putti.

02:44:36.780 --> 02:44:39.930
A lot of people refer to
them as cherubs but putti.

02:44:39.930 --> 02:44:41.850
And they're like little babies.

02:44:41.850 --> 02:44:45.210
We have four and then it has
a landing and then four more.

02:44:45.210 --> 02:44:47.450
So we have eight on the
right, eight on the left.

02:44:47.450 --> 02:44:50.300
I'm going to talk
about four on my left

02:44:50.300 --> 02:44:51.880
if we're in the building.

02:44:51.880 --> 02:44:54.070
&gt;&gt; Do you [inaudible]?

02:44:54.070 --> 02:44:55.370
No?

02:44:55.370 --> 02:44:56.670
&gt;&gt; Katharine Tuchman: No.

02:44:56.670 --> 02:44:57.970
That's [inaudible].

02:44:57.970 --> 02:45:01.300
Yeah, when you're going up the
side, the putti or in little --

02:45:01.300 --> 02:45:04.560
what I would call like a
window, like a little house.

02:45:04.560 --> 02:45:06.560
There are four of them,
and they're aligned

02:45:06.560 --> 02:45:07.860
up next to each other.

02:45:07.860 --> 02:45:11.220
The first one is sitting there
on his knees facing us directly.

02:45:11.220 --> 02:45:13.990
In his right hand he
has a rake and a hoe,

02:45:13.990 --> 02:45:16.030
in his left hand he
has a watering can.

02:45:16.030 --> 02:45:18.430
And we can actually see
the water coming out of it.

02:45:18.430 --> 02:45:19.730
So he would be our what?

02:45:19.730 --> 02:45:22.240
So our gardener, correct?

02:45:22.240 --> 02:45:27.460
Next going up to would be
our -- he has an angle to us,

02:45:27.460 --> 02:45:28.760
this next little [inaudible].

02:45:28.760 --> 02:45:31.180
He would be facing the left.

02:45:31.180 --> 02:45:33.340
His left hand is
reaching out of his house,

02:45:33.340 --> 02:45:34.640
trying to get to the gardener.

02:45:34.640 --> 02:45:38.300
And in his right hand, behind
him, is a butterfly net.

02:45:38.300 --> 02:45:40.600
And he, of course,
is our entomologist.

02:45:40.600 --> 02:45:42.880
So we're showing
with the [inaudible]

02:45:42.880 --> 02:45:45.010
that different occupations,

02:45:45.010 --> 02:45:47.990
different hobbies are
all represented here.

02:45:47.990 --> 02:45:50.540
And this is a fantastic thing,
especially with kids, to come

02:45:50.540 --> 02:45:52.880
and they can interact and
try to show them which --

02:45:52.880 --> 02:45:54.800
you know, what do you think
this [inaudible] does?

02:45:54.800 --> 02:45:59.040
Look at the -- look
at the clues.

02:45:59.040 --> 02:46:00.340
But with the touch history,

02:46:00.340 --> 02:46:03.180
I like to give a little
bit more description.

02:46:03.180 --> 02:46:06.040
The last two, one would be,
of course, sitting there --

02:46:06.040 --> 02:46:08.390
the last [inaudible] would be
sitting there with his book

02:46:08.390 --> 02:46:11.370
on his lap, his head is
down, and he's studying.

02:46:11.370 --> 02:46:14.720
He's our scholar, because we, of
course, have to have a scholar.

02:46:14.720 --> 02:46:19.970
And last but not least on this
group would be our printer,

02:46:19.970 --> 02:46:22.900
because where would we be at the
library without the printing.

02:46:22.900 --> 02:46:26.350
So we have those on either
side of the building, going up,

02:46:26.350 --> 02:46:30.250
and it's a great opportunity to
be expansive in our description

02:46:30.250 --> 02:46:32.840
with our visitors who
have visual impairments,

02:46:32.840 --> 02:46:34.740
and also with kids when
they come into the building,

02:46:34.740 --> 02:46:36.350
we can bring the building
to life with them.

02:46:36.350 --> 02:46:40.840
Last thing I want to
mention about the Great Hall.

02:46:40.840 --> 02:46:43.760
Did I mention that you
can park about 10 cars

02:46:43.760 --> 02:46:45.640
in the floor of our Great Hall?

02:46:45.640 --> 02:46:47.750
That's kind of a fun
thing to mention.

02:46:47.750 --> 02:46:49.720
Gives you a sense of the size.

02:46:49.720 --> 02:46:54.840
Across from us, I told you about
the staircases, but directly

02:46:54.840 --> 02:46:56.950
across from arches
that we're standing at,

02:46:56.950 --> 02:46:58.900
we have three more arches.

02:46:58.900 --> 02:47:01.400
And I need to mention the
two -- the middle arch,

02:47:01.400 --> 02:47:06.370
we have the scholars, the
young and the old scholar,

02:47:06.370 --> 02:47:07.930
those are important to mention.

02:47:07.930 --> 02:47:09.230
They stand six feet in height.

02:47:09.230 --> 02:47:12.580
The young scholar was
on our left hand side,

02:47:12.580 --> 02:47:15.250
he's actually leaning
into his left arm,

02:47:15.250 --> 02:47:17.760
he's got his left leg crossed
behind him, and he's looking off

02:47:17.760 --> 02:47:20.740
to his right and his
paper that he's holding.

02:47:20.740 --> 02:47:23.360
And, of course, he's learning.

02:47:23.360 --> 02:47:26.780
And on the right hand
side is our older scholar.

02:47:26.780 --> 02:47:28.790
And we know he's older
because has a beard,

02:47:28.790 --> 02:47:31.940
his skin is a little bit looser.

02:47:31.940 --> 02:47:34.040
And he has a tablet.

02:47:34.040 --> 02:47:37.190
And of course when the building
was built they might have been

02:47:37.190 --> 02:47:39.820
implying that the young scholar
had the newer technology,

02:47:39.820 --> 02:47:42.790
the paper, and the older
scholar had the old technology,

02:47:42.790 --> 02:47:44.400
it's a little tablet.

02:47:44.400 --> 02:47:45.930
But as I like to say
to my tourists today,

02:47:45.930 --> 02:47:50.770
that the older scholar really
has the latest technology,

02:47:50.770 --> 02:47:52.070
correct?

02:47:52.070 --> 02:47:53.370
[Inaudible].

02:47:53.370 --> 02:47:55.130
But to finish a bit of our
tour -- oh, did I hit that?

02:47:55.130 --> 02:47:59.800
To [inaudible] our tour, I would
take us to our left hand side,

02:47:59.800 --> 02:48:02.820
out of the Great Hall, into
the Hall of the Education,

02:48:02.820 --> 02:48:04.120
into the hall of family.

02:48:04.120 --> 02:48:07.500
And I like to mention this hall
because this one, you come in,

02:48:07.500 --> 02:48:10.500
it's about 70 feet
long, 20 feet wide,

02:48:10.500 --> 02:48:15.600
and it's about 26
feet tall, about.

02:48:15.600 --> 02:48:17.680
It's got an archway,
which is where some

02:48:17.680 --> 02:48:19.960
of these beautiful
mosaics come in.

02:48:19.960 --> 02:48:22.230
And our mosaics are
not only decorative,

02:48:22.230 --> 02:48:24.570
but they also have
information in them.

02:48:24.570 --> 02:48:27.990
In our ceiling, since this
is the hall of the family,

02:48:27.990 --> 02:48:29.820
we have great educators.

02:48:29.820 --> 02:48:32.530
And in 1897 the librarian,

02:48:32.530 --> 02:48:36.140
the very first name
is Howe, H-O-W-E.

02:48:36.140 --> 02:48:39.740
Has anybody ever heard of
Howe, Samuel Gridley Howe?

02:48:39.740 --> 02:48:41.230
Some of us have.

02:48:41.230 --> 02:48:43.650
Samuel Gridley Howe was
the first superintendant

02:48:43.650 --> 02:48:46.150
of the Perkins School
for the Blind,

02:48:46.150 --> 02:48:47.890
which is important to note.

02:48:47.890 --> 02:48:50.350
Next to his name is
Guiadette [assumed spelling],

02:48:50.350 --> 02:48:52.710
which was the first
superintendant

02:48:52.710 --> 02:48:54.010
for the School for the Deaf.

02:48:54.010 --> 02:48:56.710
So in 1897 both the blind

02:48:56.710 --> 02:48:58.890
and the deaf were
listed in our building.

02:48:58.890 --> 02:49:00.500
I think it's important.

02:49:00.500 --> 02:49:02.060
There's also -- I have

02:49:02.060 --> 02:49:05.390
to mention this alcove is the
listing of all the librarians

02:49:05.390 --> 02:49:08.310
of Congress that we have, which
I love to mention on our tour.

02:49:08.310 --> 02:49:11.930
And our visitors are allowed
to go up and feel this.

02:49:11.930 --> 02:49:13.770
We're -- when the
building opened

02:49:13.770 --> 02:49:17.160
in 1897 we had only one
woman's name in the building,

02:49:17.160 --> 02:49:20.920
it was 1897, and that was
Sapho [assumed spelling].

02:49:20.920 --> 02:49:25.640
As of last year we now
have a second name,

02:49:25.640 --> 02:49:28.970
Dr. Carla Hayden is
engraved in our building,

02:49:28.970 --> 02:49:30.740
so it's really fantastic.

02:49:30.740 --> 02:49:34.590
So I hope you enjoyed
my little brief tour,

02:49:34.590 --> 02:49:37.060
and the wonderful opportunities
that we have to engage

02:49:37.060 --> 02:49:38.730
with visitors in a
whole different way.

02:49:38.730 --> 02:49:41.950
And if you didn't get to see the
cart, it's -- we still have it.

02:49:41.950 --> 02:49:43.750
So thank you very much.

02:49:43.750 --> 02:49:51.060
[ Applause ]

02:49:51.060 --> 02:49:52.360
&gt;&gt; Lee Ann Potter:
Thank you, Kathy.

02:49:52.360 --> 02:49:55.130
So the Thomas Jefferson building
that Kathy has been telling you

02:49:55.130 --> 02:49:59.270
about welcomes about 1.5
million visitors a year.

02:49:59.270 --> 02:50:02.580
And a few thousand of those
visitors make their way

02:50:02.580 --> 02:50:06.060
into our Young Readers
Center, which is also a part

02:50:06.060 --> 02:50:07.360
of the Library of Congress.

02:50:07.360 --> 02:50:10.580
And every Friday
morning at 10:30,

02:50:10.580 --> 02:50:14.670
if you want to see something
pretty spectacular, you can come

02:50:14.670 --> 02:50:17.990
to infant and toddler story
time at the Library of Congress.

02:50:17.990 --> 02:50:20.200
And it's unlike any
other program

02:50:20.200 --> 02:50:21.500
that happens here
at the Library.

02:50:21.500 --> 02:50:23.340
And you might say it's
a little bit louder,

02:50:23.340 --> 02:50:27.070
and some might describe as
being a little more chaotic.

02:50:27.070 --> 02:50:31.340
But late this summer,
early this fall,

02:50:31.340 --> 02:50:34.810
I was over in our Young Readers
Center, and my colleague,

02:50:34.810 --> 02:50:37.800
Sasha Dowdy, and our
intern at the time,

02:50:37.800 --> 02:50:39.530
Erin Durham [assumed
spelling], who is a student

02:50:39.530 --> 02:50:42.590
at the University of
Maryland, they were practicing

02:50:42.590 --> 02:50:45.520
for the upcoming story time.

02:50:45.520 --> 02:50:48.350
And, you know, story time
always involves songs,

02:50:48.350 --> 02:50:50.270
and there's always a
little bit of movement.

02:50:50.270 --> 02:50:53.900
But this was the first story
time that we were experimenting

02:50:53.900 --> 02:50:58.190
with bringing some musical
instruments into story time.

02:50:58.190 --> 02:51:01.790
And it was really
quite something.

02:51:01.790 --> 02:51:04.400
When you're used to see
a little bit of chaos,

02:51:04.400 --> 02:51:07.370
and suddenly a violin
is involved,

02:51:07.370 --> 02:51:09.800
three year olds are mesmerized.

02:51:09.800 --> 02:51:12.100
And so I thought it
would be kind of fun

02:51:12.100 --> 02:51:14.560
to mesmerize you guys
for a little bit today,

02:51:14.560 --> 02:51:17.920
and so I invited Sasha,
and I invited Erin to come

02:51:17.920 --> 02:51:21.960
and share a little bit of
musical story time with you.

02:51:32.580 --> 02:51:35.030
&gt;&gt; Hello. Thank you, Lee Ann.

02:51:35.030 --> 02:51:36.330
All right.

02:51:36.330 --> 02:51:37.630
So this book that
we're presenting

02:51:37.630 --> 02:51:40.510
to you today is called <i>Mole
Music </i>by David McPhail.

02:51:40.510 --> 02:51:58.270
[ Music ]

02:51:58.270 --> 02:52:00.390
Mole lived all alone
underground.

02:52:00.390 --> 02:52:03.510
He spent his days
digging tunnels.

02:52:03.510 --> 02:52:06.040
[ Music ]

02:52:06.040 --> 02:52:08.350
At night he at his
supper in front

02:52:08.350 --> 02:52:11.510
of TV and then went to bed.

02:52:11.510 --> 02:52:14.140
[ Music ]

02:52:14.140 --> 02:52:17.140
Mole liked his life, but
lately he had begun to feel

02:52:17.140 --> 02:52:19.510
that there was something
missing.

02:52:19.510 --> 02:52:24.180
[ Music ]

02:52:24.180 --> 02:52:27.050
One night on the television
a man played the violin.

02:52:27.050 --> 02:52:30.510
He made the most beautiful
music mole had ever heard.

02:52:30.510 --> 02:52:40.380
[ Music ]

02:52:40.380 --> 02:52:44.510
I want to make beautiful music,
too, Mole said to himself.

02:52:44.510 --> 02:52:49.090
[ Music ]

02:52:49.090 --> 02:52:53.510
So the next day he sent away
for a violin of his own.

02:52:53.510 --> 02:52:56.130
[ Music ]

02:52:56.130 --> 02:52:59.510
Every day Mole checked
his mailbox.

02:52:59.510 --> 02:53:02.040
[ Music ]

02:53:02.040 --> 02:53:04.270
No violin.

02:53:04.270 --> 02:53:06.520
[ Music ]

02:53:06.520 --> 02:53:10.510
Finally, after nearly
three weeks, it arrived.

02:53:10.510 --> 02:53:13.050
[ Music ]

02:53:13.050 --> 02:53:15.510
Mole was so excited!

02:53:15.510 --> 02:53:20.560
[ Music ]

02:53:20.560 --> 02:53:24.510
He picked up the violin and
drew the bow across the strings.

02:53:24.510 --> 02:53:28.140
[ Music ]

02:53:28.140 --> 02:53:29.660
But instead of beautiful music,

02:53:29.660 --> 02:53:32.410
all he made was a
horrible screeching sound.

02:53:32.410 --> 02:53:34.800
[ Music ]

02:53:34.800 --> 02:53:36.580
Mole tried again.

02:53:36.580 --> 02:53:39.060
[ Music ]

02:53:39.060 --> 02:53:44.060
The violin still screeched,
but not quite so horribly.

02:53:44.060 --> 02:53:46.430
Mole kept at it.

02:53:46.430 --> 02:53:49.050
After about a week he
could play one note.

02:53:49.050 --> 02:53:51.080
[ Music ]

02:53:51.080 --> 02:53:52.380
Then two.

02:53:52.380 --> 02:53:54.060
[ Music ]

02:53:54.060 --> 02:53:58.510
And before a month went by,
he could play an entire scale.

02:53:58.510 --> 02:54:02.050
[ Music ]

02:54:02.050 --> 02:54:04.030
Mole continued to practice.

02:54:04.030 --> 02:54:06.040
[ Music ]

02:54:06.040 --> 02:54:09.510
He learned to put the notes
together in a simple song.

02:54:09.510 --> 02:54:14.500
[ Music ]

02:54:14.500 --> 02:54:16.510
Years went by.

02:54:16.510 --> 02:54:20.060
[ Music ]

02:54:20.060 --> 02:54:23.510
Mole got better and better.

02:54:23.510 --> 02:54:26.300
[ Music ]

02:54:26.300 --> 02:54:28.800
He was happier than
he had ever been.

02:54:28.800 --> 02:54:32.200
During the day as he dug tunnels
Mole hummed the music he would

02:54:32.200 --> 02:54:34.000
play at night.

02:54:34.000 --> 02:54:41.440
[ Music ]

02:54:41.440 --> 02:54:43.150
Now Mole played even better

02:54:43.150 --> 02:54:46.510
than the man he had
seen on TV so long ago.

02:54:46.510 --> 02:54:54.120
[ Music ]

02:54:54.120 --> 02:54:55.800
Sometimes he wondered
what it would be

02:54:55.800 --> 02:54:59.510
like to play his
music for people.

02:54:59.510 --> 02:55:05.220
[ Music ]

02:55:05.220 --> 02:55:08.510
He imagined himself playing
before a huge audience.

02:55:08.510 --> 02:55:15.040
[ Music ]

02:55:15.040 --> 02:55:18.510
He imagined that he played
for presidents and queens.

02:55:18.510 --> 02:55:23.400
[ Music ]

02:55:23.400 --> 02:55:26.170
He even imagined that
his music could reach

02:55:26.170 --> 02:55:30.510
into people's hearts, and melt
away their anger and sadness.

02:55:30.510 --> 02:55:34.270
[ Music ]

02:55:34.270 --> 02:55:38.510
Why maybe his music could
even change the world.

02:55:38.510 --> 02:55:44.510
[ Music ]

02:55:44.510 --> 02:55:46.510
Mole laughed at himself.

02:55:46.510 --> 02:55:50.040
[ Music ]

02:55:50.040 --> 02:55:51.620
How silly I am, he thought,

02:55:51.620 --> 02:55:54.050
imagining that my music
could do all that,

02:55:54.050 --> 02:55:56.510
when no one has ever
even heard it.

02:55:56.510 --> 02:56:04.040
[ Music ]

02:56:04.040 --> 02:56:06.510
Mole played one more song.

02:56:06.510 --> 02:56:20.510
[ Music ]

02:56:20.510 --> 02:56:23.820
Then he put down his
violin and went to sleep

02:56:23.820 --> 02:56:27.030
and dreamed beautiful
peaceful dreams.

02:56:27.030 --> 02:56:29.040
[ Music ]

02:56:29.040 --> 02:56:30.840
The end.

02:56:30.840 --> 02:56:34.510
[ Music ]

02:56:34.510 --> 02:56:47.350
[ Applause ]

